00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:30.540
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. In recent years, we've seen the rise of populist authoritarians

00:01:30.540 --> 00:01:36.020
[Amit Varma]: across the world. Trump in the US, Erdogan in Turkey, Orban in Hungary, Modi in India.

00:01:36.020 --> 00:01:39.700
[Amit Varma]: What do they have in common? Well, the author Jean-Werner Muller wrote a book a couple of

00:01:39.700 --> 00:01:43.580
[Amit Varma]: years ago where he pointed out a number of things that populists tend to have in common.

00:01:43.580 --> 00:01:46.820
[Amit Varma]: I wrote a column on the book for the Times of India, which is linked on the page for

00:01:46.820 --> 00:01:52.600
[Amit Varma]: this episode. One of the things he pointed out is that populists tend to try and consolidate

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:59.300
[Amit Varma]: their power by undermining the rules and institutions that otherwise act as a check on them. These

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:03.820
[Amit Varma]: rules and institutions are the subject of our show today. My guest on the show is Amaya

00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:08.340
[Amit Varma]: Naik, who is a lawyer and policy analyst, a graduate of the Fletcher School of Law and

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:13.340
