00:03:37.460 --> 00:03:41.060
[Amit Varma]: Hi Amit, it's good to be here. Ameya, if you know if you ask young kids at

00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:44.180
[Amit Varma]: the age of 10, what do you want to be when you grow up and they'll say all kinds of things,

00:03:44.180 --> 00:03:47.060
[Amit Varma]: you know, they want to be astronauts or they want to be rock stars or they want to be even

00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:51.300
[Amit Varma]: engineers or doctors if they're too influenced by their parents. Very few people kids say

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:55.180
[Amit Varma]: hey, I want to grow up and be a policy analyst and I want to specialize in international

00:03:55.180 --> 00:04:00.380
[Amit Varma]: relations. How did you get into all this? So if you asked me at 10, I'm guessing my

00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:04.340
[Guest]: answer would have been something like I want to be a lawyer. And you are a lawyer. And

00:04:04.340 --> 00:04:09.820
[Guest]: I did I did go to law school. I'm a lapsed lawyer. I've never practiced in part because

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:14.660
[Guest]: the kind of law I specialize in is public international law, which means not people

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:22.060
[Guest]: but states are parties. I guess I read a lot of like, it's like thrillers, but more about

00:04:22.060 --> 00:04:27.380
[Guest]: negotiation and diplomacy than about spies and shooting. That was one part of it. So

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:34.260
[Guest]: like not John le Carre, but Morgenthau. Yeah, there's fiction to be had in the diplomacy

00:04:34.260 --> 00:04:42.980
[Guest]: space as well. I did a bunch of like debates and model UNs and things in school and I remember

00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:47.620
[Guest]: just being you know, the experience of playing diplomat for a day was fascinating enough

00:04:47.620 --> 00:04:51.420
[Guest]: that I was like, this might be what I actually want to do with my life. In India, that's

00:04:51.420 --> 00:04:55.620
[Guest]: not necessarily the easiest thing to do because you sort of have exactly one professional

00:04:55.620 --> 00:05:01.900
[Guest]: path, which is get into the foreign services. And so I sort of spent college and law school

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:07.940
[Guest]: trying to do that and didn't quite make it and then had to look around and be like, okay,

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:12.060
[Guest]: so now if I want to study this professionally and find other ways and other places to do

00:05:12.060 --> 00:05:16.940
[Guest]: it, how do I go about that? And you know, that's where an international law focus and

00:05:16.940 --> 00:05:18.740
[Guest]: sort of policy analysis of the field grows in.

00:05:18.740 --> 00:05:24.700
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when you started studying, say, international relations and international

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:29.740
[Amit Varma]: law and so on and so forth, and you look through the last from the time India has been independent

00:05:29.740 --> 00:05:33.820
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, what are the kind of coherent themes or strands that emerge?

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:38.100
[Guest]: Well, especially given the episode we're going to do this, there's obviously a strand around

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:42.580
[Guest]: the development of a liberal institutional order, especially post World War Two, you

00:05:42.580 --> 00:05:47.460
[Guest]: really can't escape nuclear non proliferation and disarmament as a theme. And it's a big

00:05:47.460 --> 00:05:52.500
[Guest]: one both in its successes and its failures. You know, if you want the jargon term for

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:58.140
[Guest]: it hegemonic transition is the third one. So how the US rises from the ashes of the

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:03.660
[Guest]: British Empire. Superbook, you can read about this, by the way, it's called Safe Passage

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:11.020
[Guest]: by Corey Shawkey on precisely the peaceful transition of power from the British to the

00:06:11.020 --> 00:06:15.820
[Guest]: United States peaceful within quarts because you know, World Wars, and now potentially

00:06:15.820 --> 00:06:20.660
[Guest]: with China rising, what might the next hegemonic transition look like?

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:25.260
[Amit Varma]: And you know, what we're talking about, obviously, is a sort of in a sense impelled by the rise

00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:31.500
[Amit Varma]: of authoritarian leaders, like Trump and Orban and Erdogan, and to some extent, Modi and

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:35.820
[Amit Varma]: I'd once written a column last year about populism, which looked at John Werner Muller's

00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:41.980
[Amit Varma]: book about populism, and he identified seven or eight things that populist leaders had

00:06:41.980 --> 00:06:47.140
[Amit Varma]: in common. And one of them, which all of these people we named have have in common is that

00:06:47.140 --> 00:06:53.140
[Amit Varma]: they immediately start attacking and eroding institutions. And it's almost as if you know,

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:57.380
[Amit Varma]: guys like Trump believe that democracy is all about elections. And that's it, you win

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:01.740
[Amit Varma]: that particular beauty contest, and you're king for five years and nothing else matters.

00:07:01.740 --> 00:07:06.940
[Amit Varma]: But actually, democracy is a lot more than that, as much as the act of the people expressing

00:07:06.940 --> 00:07:12.380
[Amit Varma]: themselves through voting. It's the you know, the rules and institutions matter a great

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:17.460
[Amit Varma]: deal. Why is that? How did this understanding evolved at rules and institutions matter?

00:07:17.460 --> 00:07:20.740
[Amit Varma]: How do we design a system of government?

00:07:20.740 --> 00:07:24.820
[Guest]: It's a great question. First of all, you're absolutely right that democracy is a lot more

00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:29.860
[Guest]: than just voting. Voting is a lot more than just voting. There's a whole bunch of systems

00:07:29.860 --> 00:07:34.500
[Guest]: around on, you know, who gets to vote and how much each vote counts for and how the

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:36.300
[Guest]: votes are counted.

00:07:36.300 --> 00:07:38.020
[Guest]: Public choice theory.

00:07:38.020 --> 00:07:41.860
[Guest]: Whether it's machines doing them or humans and so on and so forth. None of those are

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:46.740
[Guest]: trivial decisions. But zoom out to sort of the big philosophical question, right? In

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:50.620
[Guest]: a sense, what you're asking is, do we need governments? And why do we need them? And

00:07:50.620 --> 00:07:55.980
[Guest]: I would say, yes, we need them. And we need them because there are a set of problems that

00:07:55.980 --> 00:07:59.420
[Guest]: individuals acting in their own best self interest, unfortunately, are not able to solve.

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:03.300
[Amit Varma]: I think we all kind of agree that we need them. But then the question is, how do they

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:05.580
[Amit Varma]: evolve? And how can they be designed?

00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:09.380
[Guest]: You know, if you take as a given that basically, the goal of a government is to solve collective

00:08:09.380 --> 00:08:14.260
[Guest]: action problems, right? It's to solve situations where each individual person finds themselves

00:08:14.260 --> 00:08:18.660
[Guest]: in what you know, what game theory would call a prisoner's dilemma. If everybody cooperates,

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:23.180
[Guest]: you're going to do better. But really, you have a higher payoff right now for defecting

00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:29.260
[Guest]: rather than cooperating. So again, phenomenal book you can read. This one's old. It's by

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:32.140
[Guest]: Robert Axelrod. It's called the evolution of cooperation.

00:08:32.140 --> 00:08:35.700
[Amit Varma]: Evolution of cooperation. One of my favorite books and one of my recent guests, Matt Ridley

00:08:35.700 --> 00:08:40.020
[Amit Varma]: talks about as well. And Ridley, in fact, was I did a recent episode with him where

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:43.860
[Amit Varma]: he was talking about the evolution of government. And he said that all governments or the state

00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:49.300
[Amit Varma]: essentially first began as a protection racket. And then they evolved to other things. So

00:08:49.300 --> 00:08:53.220
[Amit Varma]: what you're talking about, you know, all this collective action and looking after rights

00:08:53.220 --> 00:08:57.100
[Amit Varma]: as classical liberals would say and all that is kind of post facto rationalizations. It

00:08:57.100 --> 00:09:01.980
[Amit Varma]: begin as protection rackets. And then we've, you know, figured out how do we rationalize

00:09:01.980 --> 00:09:08.580
[Amit Varma]: it and then how do we bring it under control? I mean, one of the great dilemmas of any society

00:09:08.580 --> 00:09:13.860
[Amit Varma]: is that you want the government to serve the society instead of the other way around.

00:09:13.860 --> 00:09:18.900
[Guest]: That's exactly right. So this is a famous school in political science and political

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:25.540
[Guest]: theory, right? Best developed by Charles Tilley in politics and Mancur Olson in economics.

00:09:25.540 --> 00:09:31.140
[Guest]: Tilley's essay is famously war making and state making as organized crime. And it's

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:35.900
[Guest]: right. It's sort of the function that it served was, hey, I'm a feudal lord. I'm going to

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:40.100
[Guest]: stop other feudal lords from raising you. And Olson's book, in fact, was called Stationery

00:09:40.100 --> 00:09:45.840
[Guest]: Bandits. Exactly. But let's make a distinction here between sort of the historical reason

00:09:45.840 --> 00:09:50.860
[Guest]: that governments evolve. Absolutely. And the theoretical function that rules or institutions

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:56.780
[Guest]: serve, right? And so on the latter on the on the theoretical function that they serve,

00:09:56.780 --> 00:10:03.660
[Guest]: it is precisely that if you let the guy in power do whatever he or she wants, then that

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:08.900
[Guest]: person is going to do things that are good for them and not necessarily for the people

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:15.260
[Guest]: in whose interest they are supposed to be acting. And the reason that Axelrod's work

00:10:15.260 --> 00:10:20.980
[Guest]: is just so defining of the field is because he shows that if you actually play out that

00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:25.700
[Guest]: game and by the way, he did this by mailing a version of that game to a bunch of people

00:10:25.700 --> 00:10:31.260
[Guest]: and asking them to play it. There is a clear superior strategy that emerges. That strategy

00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:35.460
[Guest]: is what he calls nice tit for tat. Right? Start by assuming the other guy will play

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:41.500
[Guest]: by the rules. If they don't punish them as you go on punishing them, that sort of devolves

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:45.140
[Guest]: into a situation where clearly you're not able to work together. If they do continue

00:10:45.140 --> 00:10:49.860
[Guest]: cooperating and as that builds up, it goes beyond the point where you're just building

00:10:49.860 --> 00:10:54.700
[Guest]: trust between those two people related to that interaction. That trust itself becomes

00:10:54.700 --> 00:10:57.300
[Guest]: a valuable commodity that can be used to do other things.

00:10:57.300 --> 00:11:00.180
[Amit Varma]: And if I remember correctly, he termed it reciprocal altruism.

00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:05.180
[Guest]: Exactly. Right. He's, I mean, the piece of this that I find most fascinating, right,

00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:10.980
[Guest]: is at some point of time after you've had the good experience of somebody abiding by

00:11:10.980 --> 00:11:17.420
[Guest]: the rules for a number of turns, two things happen. One, those rules themselves take on

00:11:17.420 --> 00:11:21.860
[Guest]: a sort of existence of their own. Right? This is famous experiment. It's been done on the

00:11:21.860 --> 00:11:26.260
[Guest]: negative side, but it is famous experiment of like five monkeys in a cage and every time

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:29.820
[Guest]: they try to walk towards the ladder in the middle that leads up to the fruits, they get

00:11:29.820 --> 00:11:34.500
[Guest]: doused with cold water. Right? And then one of the monkeys is taken out and a new monkey

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:38.700
[Guest]: is put in. This new monkey has no idea about this cold water thing. That monkey starts

00:11:38.700 --> 00:11:43.180
[Guest]: walking towards the ladder because hey, fruits, the other four will jump and pull it back

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:47.060
[Guest]: before it gets anywhere near the ladder because they know what's going to happen. Then you

00:11:47.060 --> 00:11:52.620
[Guest]: have three old monkeys, two new monkeys, two old monkeys, three new monkeys, four, five

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:56.940
[Guest]: new monkeys, none of which have experienced cold water and yet they pull each other back,

00:11:56.940 --> 00:12:00.660
[Guest]: but they know that there's a rule. The rule is if you go close to the ladder, something

00:12:00.660 --> 00:12:04.900
[Amit Varma]: bad will happen. We don't let that happen. Right. And you know, and conservatives would

00:12:04.900 --> 00:12:08.220
[Amit Varma]: love this because it tells you that rules evolve for a reason. Traditions evolve for

00:12:08.220 --> 00:12:15.180
[Guest]: a reason. Absolutely. No. And you know, it might not be as blatant as you will experience

00:12:15.180 --> 00:12:17.500
[Guest]: something unpleasant if you try to go and grab that reward.

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:20.820
[Amit Varma]: And the reason may not always be a nice thing. Here it's you want to avoid cold water, but

00:12:20.820 --> 00:12:24.060
[Amit Varma]: you know, you have other kinds of impulses and instincts.

00:12:24.060 --> 00:12:29.380
[Guest]: But the insight is that there are some things that we don't mess with because we know that

00:12:29.380 --> 00:12:32.880
[Guest]: there are going to be negative consequences. In a game that's played out long enough with

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:39.380
[Guest]: enough trust builds out, the rule actually takes on that sort of existence of its own.

00:12:39.380 --> 00:12:44.220
[Guest]: You know, if you read like Fraser's work in sociology on like the evolution of religion,

00:12:44.220 --> 00:12:49.700
[Guest]: for instance, it's precisely that first it's the divine that's sacred, then it's the rules

00:12:49.700 --> 00:12:53.140
[Guest]: that you have to follow in interacting with the divine that becomes sacred. Eventually,

00:12:53.140 --> 00:12:56.140
[Guest]: you know, the divine is forgotten, but the rules and the people who enforce them still

00:12:56.140 --> 00:13:01.180
[Guest]: have sacred authority. You could substitute government for sacred authority there if you

00:13:01.180 --> 00:13:04.980
[Guest]: like. Right. The church is one form of government in itself. And the government is one form

00:13:04.980 --> 00:13:09.520
[Guest]: of religion. And the government is a form of religion in itself as well. So as I said,

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:12.820
[Guest]: one thing that happens is that the rules take on a life of their own. The other thing that

00:13:12.820 --> 00:13:18.380
[Guest]: happens is that there is a sort of social and political capital that emerges. And somebody

00:13:18.380 --> 00:13:24.820
[Guest]: who's a reasonably talented political entrepreneur can say, here is this other risky area where

00:13:24.820 --> 00:13:29.940
[Guest]: we haven't really solved this cooperation problem yet. But you know that you can trust

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:34.500
[Guest]: me from this other arena. So come let's try and do this here as well. Right. And this

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:38.980
[Guest]: is a development of alliances as a concept over a period of time. And so what you get

00:13:38.980 --> 00:13:43.580
[Guest]: is you get these rules that stand on their own and then you get these institutions that

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:49.020
[Guest]: are built on a shared understanding of the rules and on a shared set of values that,

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:53.460
[Guest]: you know, are the philosophical equivalent of we don't go near that ladder. So your insight

00:13:53.460 --> 00:13:56.940
[Amit Varma]: really here is like, you know, when I read Axelrod first and I read about all of this

00:13:56.940 --> 00:14:01.740
[Amit Varma]: work and Robert Rivers work and so on, and my sense was, okay, this really explains how

00:14:01.740 --> 00:14:05.940
[Amit Varma]: society works or cooperation within society works. But what you're putting out is that

00:14:05.940 --> 00:14:11.220
[Amit Varma]: these rules that emerge lead to institutions, and then whatever government forms, whatever

00:14:11.220 --> 00:14:15.860
[Amit Varma]: the state is, they have to abide by these rules in these institutions. And at some point,

00:14:15.860 --> 00:14:20.140
[Amit Varma]: they get codified and they become part of the law or the constitution or whatever. And

00:14:20.140 --> 00:14:24.780
[Amit Varma]: these are the rules of the game and that they evolved first and the state came later. Is

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:30.400
[Guest]: that sort of a correct understanding of it? Again, I mean, let's keep the conceptual apart

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:34.100
[Guest]: from the historic, right? If you're going to look at the timeline, they probably evolved

00:14:34.100 --> 00:14:40.220
[Guest]: co-evilly at the same time, you know, and they didn't evolve in silos, right? Like,

00:14:40.220 --> 00:14:46.700
[Guest]: not every country had to go through the collapse of the Soviet Union to decide that fully planned

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:51.300
[Guest]: system of government was not necessarily a bright idea. And so there is an element of

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:58.280
[Guest]: vicarious learning that goes on as well. But certainly, if you're going to talk about laws,

00:14:58.280 --> 00:15:03.940
[Guest]: I think that that timeline holds, that there were rules and norms and sort of soft customs

00:15:03.940 --> 00:15:09.140
[Guest]: or something before eventually somebody codified them. And they got formal sanction behind

00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:10.140
[Guest]: them and they became laws.

00:15:10.140 --> 00:15:14.340
[Amit Varma]: And if you just look at the foundation of the United States of America, for example,

00:15:14.340 --> 00:15:19.140
[Amit Varma]: there was this value, for example, for individual freedom, for the pursuit of happiness, all

00:15:19.140 --> 00:15:23.180
[Amit Varma]: the things laid out in the Declaration of Independence were already values that were

00:15:23.180 --> 00:15:29.020
[Amit Varma]: being articulated by the people. And that led to a system of government where you had

00:15:29.020 --> 00:15:34.900
[Amit Varma]: those rules and institutions in place to protect citizens from the state, which is, you know,

00:15:34.900 --> 00:15:39.100
[Amit Varma]: a key purpose of the rules and the institutions. For example, you had the Constitution that

00:15:39.100 --> 00:15:42.820
[Amit Varma]: was really your set of rules and you had the First Amendment protecting everybody's free

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:47.460
[Amit Varma]: speech and blah, blah, blah, all the way down the line. And all of that kind of falls into

00:15:47.460 --> 00:15:53.400
[Amit Varma]: place. But in sort of other states across time, like if you look at India's formation,

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:59.260
[Amit Varma]: what we really did was we adopted a hodgepodge of rules and laws from everywhere. We kept

00:15:59.260 --> 00:16:04.260
[Amit Varma]: a lot of the colonial rules that had been formulated in the first place to suppress

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:10.900
[Amit Varma]: a populace. And you know, the rules and institutions for that reason in India aren't so robust

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:15.860
[Amit Varma]: and aren't so liberal, as for example, they are in the USA evolved differently in different

00:16:15.860 --> 00:16:22.460
[Amit Varma]: places. So what are those sort of do those processes move in a particular direction necessarily?

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:28.620
[Amit Varma]: And can we pass a value judgment on the process? What if the rules that a constitution sets

00:16:28.620 --> 00:16:32.620
[Amit Varma]: merely reflect the norms of that particular society?

00:16:32.620 --> 00:16:37.920
[Guest]: So, you know, the first half of that question of like, do these processes move in a specific

00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:43.260
[Guest]: direction or predictable trajectory is an easy one. The answer is no. It really is too

00:16:43.260 --> 00:16:47.620
[Guest]: generous. It really is. You know, each historical case sort of has to be dealt with on its own

00:16:47.620 --> 00:16:48.620
[Amit Varma]: merits.

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:53.940
[Amit Varma]: There's no arc of history here, which always goes in the same direction, the arc of justice.

00:16:53.940 --> 00:17:01.220
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I wish the answer was yes, right. But clearly, from what we see, I mean, so

00:17:01.220 --> 00:17:07.380
[Guest]: again, the caveat is that more and more as we get into the 19th century and the 20th

00:17:07.380 --> 00:17:12.420
[Guest]: century and the 21st century, states are not evolving and societies are not evolving in

00:17:12.420 --> 00:17:17.860
[Guest]: isolation, right? The most closed societies on the planet right now are North Korea and

00:17:17.860 --> 00:17:24.140
[Guest]: Eritrea. Even those states are not sealed off from the world, right? Part of how Eritrea

00:17:24.140 --> 00:17:29.580
[Guest]: makes its money is by taxing overseas citizens. They are able to collect that tax because

00:17:29.580 --> 00:17:33.900
[Guest]: they threaten family members of those people who are still within the country.

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:34.900
[Guest]: Protection racket.

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:41.980
[Guest]: But protection racket in its simplest form, right? But international, right? And so, the

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:47.460
[Guest]: more that the world itself is interconnected, the more that these institutions are interconnected,

00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:54.500
[Guest]: there's something like a tipping point that comes about, right? So, the way that the institutions

00:17:54.500 --> 00:18:00.060
[Guest]: and the rules will evolve is still distinct within each country. But the range of possibilities

00:18:00.060 --> 00:18:05.780
[Guest]: that it can hold are getting progressively constrained. They're falling within a certain

00:18:05.780 --> 00:18:10.780
[Guest]: band of things that other countries share, and especially post the creation of the UN

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:15.620
[Guest]: that they have formally stated a commitment to sharing. There is a Declaration of Principles

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:22.060
[Guest]: that starts the UN Charter as well. The first of those is that every country is a sovereign

00:18:22.060 --> 00:18:29.260
[Guest]: equal and nobody shall intervene in its domestic matters. But historically, even that is quite

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:34.780
[Guest]: the exceptional commitment for a country to make, right? And clearly, many countries have

00:18:34.780 --> 00:18:39.940
[Guest]: failed to abide by it, even since the adoption of the UN Charter. But it's no longer really

00:18:39.940 --> 00:18:45.140
[Guest]: open to a country to say, you know, as part of our constitution, we're going to say, we

00:18:45.140 --> 00:18:48.820
[Guest]: espouse the virtue of territorial conquest. It won't fly.

00:18:48.820 --> 00:18:51.940
[Amit Varma]: That's because there are rules at the international level also now.

00:18:51.940 --> 00:18:56.180
[Guest]: Yes. And like, let's use that softer term rules to mean a lot of fuzzy things and a

00:18:56.180 --> 00:18:58.300
[Amit Varma]: lot of hard things. But yes, there are.

00:18:58.300 --> 00:19:02.820
[Amit Varma]: Right. And, you know, so to kind of cut to the present day, so what we've always sort

00:19:02.820 --> 00:19:09.260
[Amit Varma]: of had is that we have a bunch of these safeguards. Some of these are in the form of these rules

00:19:09.260 --> 00:19:13.380
[Amit Varma]: embedded in the constitution or the laws or whatever, which restrain a government. And

00:19:13.380 --> 00:19:19.220
[Amit Varma]: we have this bunch of institutions and limits to the sort of interplay between them to make

00:19:19.220 --> 00:19:24.980
[Amit Varma]: sure that no one institution gets too powerful or domineering. So in India, you know, you'll

00:19:24.980 --> 00:19:28.420
[Amit Varma]: have your in the US, you have your Congress and you have the Senate and the President

00:19:28.420 --> 00:19:34.380
[Amit Varma]: only has so much power and he can't really be an overlord. And by and large, have there

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:39.780
[Amit Varma]: been US presidents in the past who have because power always corrupts anyone who comes to

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:44.660
[Amit Varma]: power will want to be as powerful as he possibly can. And therefore, the urge is always going

00:19:44.660 --> 00:19:49.660
[Amit Varma]: to be to push back against these institutions and against these rules. And what's that process

00:19:49.660 --> 00:19:51.380
[Amit Varma]: been in like in America?

00:19:51.380 --> 00:19:56.860
[Guest]: Yeah, so so two things, right. One is I'm going to sort of contest the power always

00:19:56.860 --> 00:20:03.100
[Guest]: corrupts rule just my training in in base is I'm a psychologist. And there's fantastic

00:20:03.100 --> 00:20:08.540
[Guest]: research on how when you increase power distance between two people, what's happening is not

00:20:08.540 --> 00:20:12.900
[Guest]: an abandoning of values or principles. When that happens, it actually happens on the person

00:20:12.900 --> 00:20:16.540
[Guest]: who's on the low end of the power scale. The person who's on the high end of the power

00:20:16.540 --> 00:20:22.500
[Guest]: scale, what happens is a weakening of communication and empathy. And so you're on guard, and we're

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:26.220
[Guest]: sort of the father of peace research. This is really great quote that says power does

00:20:26.220 --> 00:20:33.140
[Guest]: not corrupt power obscures powerlessness corrupts. What power does is it separates you from the

00:20:33.140 --> 00:20:36.340
[Guest]: consequences of your actions. And the way that that actually happens,

00:20:36.340 --> 00:20:39.460
[Amit Varma]: which leads to a kind of moral corruption in a sense, right?

00:20:39.460 --> 00:20:43.460
[Guest]: It does. So what what happens for a lot of people is even if you believe in theory that

00:20:43.460 --> 00:20:48.620
[Guest]: the you know, the ends do not justify the means, if you can't actually observe the impact

00:20:48.620 --> 00:20:52.620
[Guest]: that the means are having, why would you believe that there's a problem with the means? That's

00:20:52.620 --> 00:20:59.460
[Guest]: a great point, right? I immediately thought of demonetization. Indeed, among other things.

00:20:59.460 --> 00:21:03.700
[Guest]: And so what happens is no, actually, that's a great example. Because what happens is that

00:21:03.700 --> 00:21:08.940
[Guest]: people who manage to hold a certain amount of power, hypothetically can have two somewhat

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:14.700
[Guest]: competing goals, right? They can have specific policy goals and outcomes that they want to

00:21:14.700 --> 00:21:18.900
[Guest]: achieve. And they can be invested in the health of the institution and the system itself.

00:21:18.900 --> 00:21:25.500
[Guest]: Right? Not every powerful person is, but many are. And in wanting to pursue or achieve a

00:21:25.500 --> 00:21:30.740
[Guest]: particular policy goal, and in sort of gathering the amount of power and doing the things that

00:21:30.740 --> 00:21:35.060
[Guest]: are necessary to see that happen, they might find that they have undermined the institutions

00:21:35.060 --> 00:21:39.060
[Guest]: and in fact done, you know, a lot more harm than they originally thought possible or set

00:21:39.060 --> 00:21:46.340
[Guest]: out to do. Obviously, the more isolated from reality, the more separated from the experience

00:21:46.340 --> 00:21:52.180
[Guest]: of the daily life of the average person, the leader is the easier this is to happen. And

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:54.540
[Guest]: so in fact, demonetization is a great example, because it's precisely

00:21:54.540 --> 00:22:00.300
[Amit Varma]: And like I talk about how Modi probably never went to a grocery store to buy something himself

00:22:00.300 --> 00:22:04.540
[Amit Varma]: for the last 20 years. And therefore he had no idea that a 2000 rupee note is actually

00:22:04.540 --> 00:22:09.740
[Amit Varma]: used by the common man. To him, it was a store of value as it indeed was in 1978. And therefore

00:22:09.740 --> 00:22:13.580
[Amit Varma]: only black money holders must be using it. But actually, everybody used it and he had

00:22:13.580 --> 00:22:19.660
[Amit Varma]: no idea because like you said, he was so insulated from the common man that I mean, it was an

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:20.660
[Amit Varma]: error in knowledge.

00:22:20.660 --> 00:22:26.860
[Guest]: Yeah, so I think that's a that's a process that we can generalize. We can say that a

00:22:26.860 --> 00:22:32.460
[Guest]: lot of people who don't necessarily say, listen, like, my goal in life is to become the Shahenshah

00:22:32.460 --> 00:22:38.140
[Guest]: still walk that path because they find that to achieve the specific policy goals that

00:22:38.140 --> 00:22:43.820
[Guest]: they want, they end up having to centralize power. Recent American history, there is no

00:22:43.820 --> 00:22:49.420
[Guest]: sort of, you know, Shakespearean tragicomic hero that illustrates this better than Barack

00:22:49.420 --> 00:22:55.780
[Guest]: Obama, who was a constitutional law professor himself, cannot have been ignorant to sort

00:22:55.780 --> 00:23:01.860
[Guest]: of the institutional ramifications of what he was doing. But at the same time was a political

00:23:01.860 --> 00:23:07.980
[Guest]: leader confronted with another branch of government that was held by the opposing party and said

00:23:07.980 --> 00:23:11.780
[Guest]: that its stated objective is to undermine everything that he does. And so it's funny

00:23:11.780 --> 00:23:17.140
[Guest]: because this guy, this guy who again is like a balance of powers enthusiast, becomes one

00:23:17.140 --> 00:23:22.220
[Guest]: of the strongest practitioners of executive power, becomes one of the most frequent users

00:23:22.220 --> 00:23:28.100
[Guest]: of executive orders in recent American history, because he's like, I can't get anything done

00:23:28.100 --> 00:23:33.980
[Guest]: otherwise. Can you elaborate on that a bit? So for instance, Obama, when he was still

00:23:33.980 --> 00:23:41.460
[Guest]: a candidate, and was running for office, was deeply critical of the wars that his predecessor

00:23:41.460 --> 00:23:47.940
[Guest]: Bush had started. Correct. Right. And he had this very lawyerly critique of them, which

00:23:47.940 --> 00:23:54.980
[Guest]: was that within American domestic law, the authority to declare war is actually vested

00:23:54.980 --> 00:23:59.500
[Guest]: in the Congress and not with the president, right? The president has authority to command

00:23:59.500 --> 00:24:04.860
[Guest]: the military, and to take actions that are necessary in defense of the country. But the

00:24:04.860 --> 00:24:10.460
[Guest]: president cannot declare that the country is at war with another sovereign power. That's

00:24:10.460 --> 00:24:15.140
[Guest]: actually for the Congress. Right? This is extremely important part of US history called

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:20.580
[Amit Varma]: the war powers resolution. And this actually tells you how an institution acts as a check

00:24:20.580 --> 00:24:24.540
[Guest]: on the overreach by any one person, for example. Absolutely, because in Congress, it would

00:24:24.540 --> 00:24:30.540
[Guest]: take a vote, right, as opposed to like an executive decision. And so his sort of very,

00:24:30.540 --> 00:24:37.100
[Guest]: as I said, very nerdy critique of the US wars in Iraq, not so much Afghanistan, but Iraq,

00:24:37.100 --> 00:24:42.260
[Guest]: was that we don't actually have proof that the party that we went after in Afghanistan

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:47.100
[Guest]: is present in Iraq, or that there's any connection between them. Hence the legal document, it's

00:24:47.100 --> 00:24:53.140
[Guest]: called an authorization for the use of military force that pertains to Afghanistan, really

00:24:53.140 --> 00:24:56.500
[Guest]: can't be transferred easily to Iraq. Okay, there's a separate authorization for the use

00:24:56.500 --> 00:25:00.700
[Guest]: of military force in Iraq, that really can't be transferred easily to Syria or to like

00:25:00.700 --> 00:25:04.540
[Guest]: wherever else we think or like Somalia or Mali or wherever we think that this group

00:25:04.540 --> 00:25:11.580
[Guest]: is cropping up, right? Obama as president oversaw a vast expansion in the number of

00:25:11.580 --> 00:25:20.900
[Guest]: military actions, not just in Afghanistan and Iraq, but in Syria, in Yemen, in Mali,

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:26.060
[Guest]: in Somalia, in Niger, that's just the countries I know about now. I'm sure that when records

00:25:26.060 --> 00:25:32.220
[Guest]: are declassified, there will be even more. One of my favourite law professors is Rosa

00:25:32.220 --> 00:25:36.900
[Guest]: Brooks at Georgetown Law. And she wrote an op-ed about this somewhere at the midpoint

00:25:36.900 --> 00:25:47.980
[Guest]: of the US presidency, which was titled AUOMFG. So she smushed together AUMF and OMFG. Just

00:25:47.980 --> 00:25:53.700
[Guest]: to say, how far are you going to stretch this authorization to like, you're in 17 countries

00:25:53.700 --> 00:26:00.180
[Guest]: when you said that it shouldn't even be two, right? And Obama's sort of dodge on this was,

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:04.700
[Guest]: I'm going to authorize drone strikes, but I'm not going to deploy. So have you heard

00:26:04.700 --> 00:26:09.460
[Guest]: the phrase boots on the ground? Yeah, of course. I'm not going to deploy boots on the ground.

00:26:09.460 --> 00:26:14.580
[Guest]: And you know, this got roundly mocked in Washington, they were like, cartoons of like, you know,

00:26:14.580 --> 00:26:19.060
[Guest]: people doing like, Tom Cruise Mission Impossible style hanging from a wire and like, my boots

00:26:19.060 --> 00:26:26.340
[Guest]: are not touching the ground. And it's just an example of there were probably more productive

00:26:26.340 --> 00:26:31.060
[Guest]: ways to handle whatever threats there were to American national security at that time,

00:26:31.060 --> 00:26:36.340
[Guest]: right? But they would have required the executive and the Congress to work together. But Obama

00:26:36.340 --> 00:26:40.900
[Guest]: found himself in a situation where having once said, no, look, it's within my power

00:26:40.900 --> 00:26:44.460
[Guest]: to decide you gave me the authorization, I'm going to target these guys, whatever these

00:26:44.460 --> 00:26:49.020
[Guest]: guys are, I can go. If he walked that back, he'd have to walk back everything else he

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:53.020
[Guest]: wanted to do as well. Right. And so it was no longer in his interest. He became a strong

00:26:53.020 --> 00:26:57.980
[Amit Varma]: executive power theorist. I mean, if he makes the same principled argument in 2007, he doesn't

00:26:57.980 --> 00:27:02.460
[Amit Varma]: become president because he's for the war on, you know, then he can't criticize George

00:27:02.460 --> 00:27:08.020
[Guest]: Bush at all on the grounds that he did. Yeah. So I, my sense is that the criticism that

00:27:08.020 --> 00:27:12.940
[Guest]: he made of the views that he espoused as a candidate were genuine and principled at the

00:27:12.940 --> 00:27:18.140
[Guest]: time at the time. And then he was confronted with the reality of having to enact security

00:27:18.140 --> 00:27:24.380
[Guest]: policy with especially post the midterms, a split government. Healthcare was originally

00:27:24.380 --> 00:27:29.940
[Guest]: introduced by executive order, right? Like massive healthcare reform in the United States

00:27:29.940 --> 00:27:34.300
[Guest]: with like the largest, I mean, by financial value, the largest healthcare industry in

00:27:34.300 --> 00:27:42.060
[Guest]: the world. Right. And you're going to reform that by fiat, like, you know, running roughshod

00:27:42.060 --> 00:27:45.900
[Guest]: over the institutions, which were there for a reason, like, forget about the effectiveness

00:27:45.900 --> 00:27:50.980
[Guest]: of it, right? Just as a matter of political strategy, it's so much weaker to be in that

00:27:50.980 --> 00:27:57.140
[Guest]: situation. Right. Right. And in fact, his successor has done his best to undermine it

00:27:57.140 --> 00:28:03.380
[Guest]: on precisely that basis. Right. And so there were a lot of people who even in, let's say,

00:28:03.380 --> 00:28:10.540
[Guest]: 2010, 2012, were already saying, listen, we're comfortable surrendering a bunch more executive

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:16.100
[Guest]: authority to this guy because it's this guy. Yeah. And we know that he's a constitutional

00:28:16.100 --> 00:28:20.140
[Guest]: law professor. And we know that, like, he agonizes over these things. And like, look,

00:28:20.140 --> 00:28:27.580
[Guest]: his hair is turning white thinking about them, literally. And but if we're not ready to do

00:28:27.580 --> 00:28:32.900
[Guest]: it for any other precedent, then, you know, we should really be careful about how much

00:28:32.900 --> 00:28:37.980
[Amit Varma]: ground are willing to give this guy. And what that kind of seems to illustrate is that the

00:28:37.980 --> 00:28:42.740
[Amit Varma]: Obama who's campaigning and the Trump who's campaigning are entirely different creatures.

00:28:42.740 --> 00:28:47.260
[Amit Varma]: But when in power, the imperatives of power, the incentives of power, what I would call

00:28:47.260 --> 00:28:51.660
[Amit Varma]: the corrupting influence of power, though you've, I mean, not in a direct way in terms

00:28:51.660 --> 00:28:58.700
[Amit Varma]: of but the kind of moral corrosion that happens, they're all the same.

00:28:58.700 --> 00:29:05.060
[Amit Varma]: So that would be true of anyone before Trump. Right. And that also leads you to a dilemma

00:29:05.060 --> 00:29:09.020
[Amit Varma]: that you know, we discuss the importance of rules and institutions. But the argument that

00:29:09.020 --> 00:29:13.780
[Amit Varma]: say Obama could have made is that look with with the kind of gridlock that there is with

00:29:13.780 --> 00:29:17.700
[Amit Varma]: the Congress and the Senate, and they're not cooperating with me on anything. I can't get

00:29:17.700 --> 00:29:22.780
[Amit Varma]: anything done because of these rules and these institutions. So therefore, I have to go past

00:29:22.780 --> 00:29:27.460
[Amit Varma]: them. How does one answer that? I mean, regardless of whether that's Obama saying that or Trump

00:29:27.460 --> 00:29:32.100
[Amit Varma]: saying that because it's the same thing being said you it's a mistake to look at the one

00:29:32.100 --> 00:29:35.500
[Amit Varma]: guy or and it's hypocritical to approve of one guy saying that and disapprove of the

00:29:35.500 --> 00:29:40.260
[Amit Varma]: other. In principle, either one agrees with it or one doesn't. I mean, one draws a line

00:29:40.260 --> 00:29:46.340
[Amit Varma]: and says that, you know, the rules and institutions are this important and no more or no less.

00:29:46.340 --> 00:29:55.700
[Guest]: How does one reconcile that? Creatively? No, I mean, again, so I like my about half the

00:29:55.700 --> 00:30:00.620
[Guest]: classes I took in graduate school were about negotiation and negotiation in like, quote

00:30:00.620 --> 00:30:05.780
[Guest]: unquote, intractable and wicked problems, right? This is one, right? Do you care about

00:30:05.780 --> 00:30:09.220
[Guest]: the policy goal? Yes, of course you do. Do you care about the health of the institution?

00:30:09.220 --> 00:30:13.700
[Guest]: Yes, of course you do. Are these two related? Yes, they are. Because if you constantly fail

00:30:13.700 --> 00:30:18.460
[Guest]: at delivering policy goals, the institution is going to be undermined in a different sense.

00:30:18.460 --> 00:30:22.940
[Guest]: Even if you're sort of complying by the rules, at some point of time, the electorate is going

00:30:22.940 --> 00:30:26.820
[Guest]: to be like these are stupid rules, right? Because nobody's able to do the things that

00:30:26.820 --> 00:30:31.700
[Amit Varma]: we need to get done. Give me a concrete illustration of this. I mean, thought experiment way, not

00:30:31.700 --> 00:30:35.100
[Guest]: something that has happened, obviously. But yeah, because I don't necessarily have one

00:30:35.100 --> 00:30:42.740
[Guest]: off the top of my head. I mean, you can imagine that actually, so most countries that have

00:30:42.740 --> 00:30:50.260
[Guest]: like a split executive and legislature have rules on the adoption of any law, right? And

00:30:50.260 --> 00:30:54.740
[Guest]: they require that a certain majority in one house and a certain majority in another house,

00:30:54.740 --> 00:31:00.380
[Guest]: then the executive gets to either sign or reject. If the executive rejects, typically,

00:31:00.380 --> 00:31:04.380
[Guest]: the legislature gets to give it another pass. If the legislature sends it back, then that

00:31:04.380 --> 00:31:08.580
[Guest]: has to be passed. If you think about it, if the outcome of this was basically that for

00:31:08.580 --> 00:31:13.500
[Guest]: like eight years, no laws were passed, I can imagine that people would sort of be like,

00:31:13.500 --> 00:31:18.420
[Guest]: okay, this is no longer working. We need to change this. We need to either like mess with

00:31:18.420 --> 00:31:23.420
[Guest]: the majority margins that are involved. Or we need to make one or the other party be

00:31:23.420 --> 00:31:28.620
[Guest]: bound by the decision of the other, right? And but the thing to keep in mind there is

00:31:28.620 --> 00:31:33.460
[Guest]: that even within the existing rules about sort of you need this much majority and you

00:31:33.460 --> 00:31:38.380
[Guest]: need this sequence of approvals. It's not like people are taking each policy issue as

00:31:38.380 --> 00:31:43.140
[Guest]: an individual thing and being like, no, but this is the exact thing that I need to happen

00:31:43.140 --> 00:31:47.740
[Guest]: on this. And this is separate from the rest of the world and the rest of politics. No,

00:31:47.740 --> 00:31:53.300
[Guest]: people are trading off their priorities on competing legislations, right? I mean, this

00:31:53.300 --> 00:31:58.740
[Guest]: sounds bad in practice, because you're like, you know, oh, if I like let you export onions,

00:31:58.740 --> 00:32:04.860
[Guest]: then you will let me allow children with disabilities to be adopted or something like that. I, you

00:32:04.860 --> 00:32:12.380
[Guest]: know, hypothetical example, but not implausible. And so, you know, we don't like to think about

00:32:12.380 --> 00:32:20.260
[Guest]: policies, being formed with this sort of like, you know, bazaar style trading of whose interests

00:32:20.260 --> 00:32:24.180
[Guest]: are what, but that's a democratic government functioning is designed.

00:32:24.180 --> 00:32:27.580
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in public choice series, there's a term called log rolling, which is about

00:32:27.580 --> 00:32:32.260
[Amit Varma]: how different interest groups, very disparate interest groups come together to increase

00:32:32.260 --> 00:32:37.020
[Amit Varma]: their bargaining power in this political marketplace, pretty much the same process playing out.

00:32:37.020 --> 00:32:42.300
[Guest]: Absolutely. And so you're seeing it play out even now where Trump is basically saying to

00:32:42.300 --> 00:32:47.740
[Guest]: his entire Congress, I want money to build a wall at the border. And I'm going to hold

00:32:47.740 --> 00:32:53.100
[Guest]: anything and everything that you'll want done hostage to this. Right? Again, it sounds like

00:32:53.100 --> 00:33:00.300
[Guest]: it sounds deeply odious to us, because the particular thing that he's holding the stuff

00:33:00.300 --> 00:33:05.420
[Guest]: hostage for is this ridiculous border wall. But he's far from the first president to say

00:33:05.420 --> 00:33:10.940
[Guest]: I'm going to hold proposals hostage to like my pet policy thing that you all have to approve,

00:33:10.940 --> 00:33:16.460
[Guest]: right? Obama also tried this with healthcare. Right? Right. Again, he failed. Congress was

00:33:16.460 --> 00:33:20.860
[Guest]: like, nope, we're like, it's a bigger priority for us to make sure that your healthcare reform

00:33:20.860 --> 00:33:26.780
[Guest]: does not pass, then that anything we want to pass does pass. And so, actually, no longer

