[Amit Varma]: the importance of rules and institutions with specific reference to the August figure of

00:35:28.220 --> 00:35:33.980
[Amit Varma]: Donald Trump. Trump fits that classic populist mold that you know, John Werner Muller wrote his

00:35:33.980 --> 00:35:38.860
[Amit Varma]: book on and that I referred to of a populist who's come and you know, he shares all the things that

00:35:38.860 --> 00:35:43.500
[Amit Varma]: populists tend to have in common through the ages and in the world today in the sense that they have

00:35:43.500 --> 00:35:48.300
[Amit Varma]: this sense of victimhood and they are ranting against the elites and they are constructing

00:35:48.300 --> 00:35:54.380
[Amit Varma]: all these simplistic narratives and they are breaking down institutions. And the interesting

00:35:54.380 --> 00:36:00.700
[Amit Varma]: thing about Trump is that this works at two levels. One, it works at the domestic level where

00:36:00.700 --> 00:36:04.700
[Amit Varma]: there are so many institutions and there is this constant interplay and like you pointed out,

00:36:04.700 --> 00:36:09.980
[Amit Varma]: he's not the first person to have, you know, tried to push those boundaries. But it's also

00:36:09.980 --> 00:36:15.020
[Amit Varma]: more worrying at the international level because the US is simply still the reigning superpower in

00:36:15.020 --> 00:36:22.060
[Amit Varma]: the world. And, you know, one mad guy on top who is trying to undermine all the international

00:36:22.060 --> 00:36:27.100
[Amit Varma]: institutions and rules which do a lot of good is extremely dangerous for all of us.

00:36:27.980 --> 00:36:33.420
[Guest]: That's exactly right. You know, I think we can we can sort of deal with each of those sequentially.

00:36:33.420 --> 00:36:42.620
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly. So, yeah, it is important to keep in mind that Trump's political beliefs don't

00:36:42.620 --> 00:36:47.020
[Guest]: necessarily make him unique, especially in the US political spectrum. There are other people who had

00:36:47.020 --> 00:36:57.900
[Guest]: those same views. His views on the US role in the international order also don't really make him

00:36:57.900 --> 00:37:04.380
[Guest]: unique. There's a smaller chunk of people that have those views. But they exist. I mean, John

00:37:04.380 --> 00:37:09.340
[Guest]: Bolton was the United States ambassador to the UN in a previous administration as well.

00:37:10.620 --> 00:37:15.020
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there have been isolationists and there have been anti free traders and all of that isn't

00:37:15.020 --> 00:37:22.860
[Guest]: really new. There are two things that make Trump unique. The first is just the fact that he actually

00:37:22.860 --> 00:37:29.580
[Guest]: got elected. Right. Because generally people who have these views haven't actually gotten into the

00:37:29.580 --> 00:37:35.980
[Guest]: most powerful seat in the country slash the world because the nature of democratic politics is to

00:37:37.180 --> 00:37:42.540
[Guest]: generally privilege moderation. Right. You need to build a broader coalition to build a broader

00:37:42.540 --> 00:37:46.780
[Amit Varma]: coalition. You need to sort of tone down your rhetoric. That's a median voter theorem where

00:37:46.780 --> 00:37:51.340
[Amit Varma]: basically all parties during the general election sort of go towards the middle. And therefore,

00:37:51.340 --> 00:37:56.300
[Amit Varma]: there is an acceptable spectrum from which all leaders tend to emerge. And then they do the same

00:37:56.300 --> 00:38:01.580
[Amit Varma]: crappy things because power corrupts. But they emerge from that limited spectrum. And Trump is

00:38:01.580 --> 00:38:08.300
[Guest]: just way out. He's an outlier in that sense. And that's why I said, you know, he's also the

00:38:08.300 --> 00:38:12.460
[Guest]: exception to like the people campaigning within the median and then like do extreme things.

00:38:12.460 --> 00:38:18.300
[Guest]: He campaigned on the extremes. Right. Right. He campaigned saying, you know, openly racist

00:38:18.300 --> 00:38:24.620
[Guest]: things about Mexicans, for instance, he campaigned accusing a judge of Mexican heritage of being

00:38:24.620 --> 00:38:29.420
[Amit Varma]: biased against him. He said Mexicans are rapists, if I remember correctly. And bringing crime and

00:38:29.420 --> 00:38:37.180
[Guest]: bringing drugs, etc, etc. So, yeah, he's unique in that he did that and won, which I currently have

00:38:37.180 --> 00:38:43.100
[Guest]: to think of as a historical accident, and which I sort of hope is a historical accident. The other

00:38:43.100 --> 00:38:51.580
[Guest]: thing that makes him unique is that, or at least unique in like modern history in the US, is that

00:38:51.580 --> 00:38:57.740
[Guest]: he is so blatantly out to enrich himself. So, you know, we said that there are institutions,

00:38:57.740 --> 00:39:02.780
[Guest]: there are rules, some of the rules are formal, so their laws, others are just norms and customs.

00:39:02.780 --> 00:39:09.500
[Guest]: If you ask sort of, why do all of these exist? They exist so that people in power will serve

00:39:09.500 --> 00:39:15.340
[Guest]: the public interest. And so sort of the, you know, almost rule zero of government is avoid

00:39:15.340 --> 00:39:21.660
[Guest]: conflicts of interest. Right. Right. Trump is like, Trump actually shares that opinion about

00:39:21.660 --> 00:39:25.900
[Guest]: we should not have a conflict of interest, but he's, you know, he's flipped it on its head.

00:39:25.900 --> 00:39:29.980
[Guest]: So he comes in saying, what is the conflict, I'm going to pursue my own personal interests,

00:39:31.100 --> 00:39:37.500
[Guest]: national interests be damned. And it's, it's pretty amazing. Like we have a number of actual

00:39:37.500 --> 00:39:42.460
[Guest]: or wannabe autocrats, right, some of whom have been elected, others have gotten power in other

00:39:42.460 --> 00:39:48.140
[Guest]: ways. Trump is a wannabe kleptocrat much more than he's a wannabe autocrat. Well said. Right?

00:39:48.140 --> 00:39:55.100
[Guest]: He's not fixated on, well, I take this back, I was going to say he's not fixated on power so much

00:39:55.100 --> 00:40:01.660
[Guest]: as he is on wealth. I'm not sure that that's a meaningful distinction in his head. So, but,

00:40:01.660 --> 00:40:06.060
[Guest]: but you know, he's, the way that he thinks about power and the way that he thinks about interest

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:11.100
[Guest]: is the accumulation of basically money for himself and his family. And I think in a way,

00:40:11.100 --> 00:40:16.300
[Amit Varma]: I see him as this megalomaniac duffer who was winging his way through life and all of this

00:40:16.300 --> 00:40:22.620
[Amit Varma]: shit just happened. And in that sense, he's both an accidental autocrat and an accidental kleptocrat.

00:40:22.620 --> 00:40:27.180
[Amit Varma]: This shit just happened. It's not like he had a grand plan and he made, I mean, he was actually

00:40:27.180 --> 00:40:31.900
[Amit Varma]: expecting, perhaps even hoping to lose the election by some accounts. And simply, I mean,

00:40:31.900 --> 00:40:36.220
[Amit Varma]: he didn't have a transition team in place. He didn't expect to be president and he's kind of

00:40:36.220 --> 00:40:42.300
[Guest]: been winging it all the way. Well, so I mean, there's multiple pieces to, by the way, before

00:40:42.300 --> 00:40:46.860
[Guest]: I get into that, right, can I just say, you know, I told you I'm a psychologist by training, right?

00:40:46.860 --> 00:40:52.860
[Guest]: And the last like century plus in psychology has basically been pushing back on this like

00:40:52.860 --> 00:40:57.660
[Guest]: great person theory of leadership. Thomas Carlyle. You know, even like, let's not fixate on the

00:40:57.660 --> 00:41:03.340
[Guest]: personality of the person in power because the situation and like sort of the exigencies and

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:09.020
[Guest]: the constraints of historical currents are what they are, are much bigger. And so it's really

00:41:09.020 --> 00:41:14.060
[Guest]: frustrating to me to have to spend this much time analyzing the personality of this guy,

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:18.460
[Guest]: because it sort of cuts in the exact opposite direction of what I've been arguing so far.

00:41:19.100 --> 00:41:26.380
[Guest]: But again, he actually did get into power. And he does believe that everything is shaped by his

00:41:26.380 --> 00:41:31.500
[Guest]: singular interests and personality. And at that point of time, I mean, it's who, Louis XIV who

00:41:31.500 --> 00:41:39.660
[Guest]: said, I am the state. Trump shares that view, but for the time being, temporarily, he's kind of

00:41:39.660 --> 00:41:44.860
[Amit Varma]: right. No, and the interesting thing is, it's not as if a leader like him was a historical

00:41:44.860 --> 00:41:49.340
[Amit Varma]: inevitability. Honestly, you take Trump out of the picture. I don't see anyone in the political

00:41:49.340 --> 00:41:54.220
[Amit Varma]: landscape who's remotely like this, you know? Yeah, I mean, yeah, Ted Cruz would have appealed

00:41:54.220 --> 00:41:58.540
[Amit Varma]: to many of the same people and could have come to power and all that. But he was essentially also a

00:41:58.540 --> 00:42:03.580
[Amit Varma]: guy who believed in these rules and institutions to some extent and accomplished lawyer himself.

00:42:03.580 --> 00:42:09.100
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you wouldn't have a complete madcap guy like Trump in power, no matter what happened.

00:42:09.100 --> 00:42:13.900
[Guest]: Yeah. Again, there are other countries that have been led by small time crooks who then become big

00:42:13.900 --> 00:42:19.020
[Guest]: time crooks. But in the current American context, it's kind of hard to imagine anybody except Trump

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:30.380
[Guest]: pulling this off. I agree. And so this is why Trump is so, so corrosive to institutions, right?

00:42:30.380 --> 00:42:35.660
[Guest]: Because the sort of again, the sort of virtue zero of all institutions in the public spaces,

00:42:36.540 --> 00:42:41.980
[Guest]: no self dealing, no conflicts of interest. And he demonstrates time and time and time again,

00:42:41.980 --> 00:42:47.820
[Guest]: that he does not share that value. He does not understand the reason or the purpose or the

00:42:47.820 --> 00:42:53.740
[Guest]: virtue of that. And so every time he interacts with any institution, he's doing it out of some

00:42:53.740 --> 00:43:01.500
[Guest]: sort of just very blatant, very crass self-interest. And he almost acts aggrieved and behaves as if

00:43:01.500 --> 00:43:06.700
[Amit Varma]: this is unfair. It's like, hey, the people elected me and now I'm the king. And, you know,

00:43:06.700 --> 00:43:12.140
[Amit Varma]: who was anyone to be a check on me? Let me do what I want. The people elected me. I have sort

00:43:12.140 --> 00:43:19.180
[Guest]: of ultimate authority. And also, isn't this what being president means is that I give orders and

00:43:19.180 --> 00:43:23.980
[Guest]: people follow them. And of course, every previous president could have told him and probably did

00:43:23.980 --> 00:43:31.020
[Guest]: tell him, no, it does not. But the man is determined to behave as if it actually is, right.

00:43:31.020 --> 00:43:37.340
[Guest]: And so there's just so many ways that this plays out in the domestic space. Right. So

00:43:37.340 --> 00:43:42.460
[Guest]: the most obvious one, again, has to do with just making money. There is a clause in the United

00:43:42.460 --> 00:43:48.940
[Guest]: States Constitution that has suddenly sort of like nobody used it, nobody heard about it. And

00:43:48.940 --> 00:43:52.380
[Guest]: then in the past couple of years, it sort of made its way back into public discourse.

00:43:52.380 --> 00:43:56.380
[Guest]: It's called the Emoluments Clause of the Constitution, right. It's roughly the same

00:43:56.380 --> 00:44:01.900
[Guest]: as like the Office of Profit Act that India had. It basically said, if you are a functionary of

00:44:01.900 --> 00:44:07.980
[Guest]: government, you should not be making money on the side. The Emoluments Clause is a little more

00:44:07.980 --> 00:44:13.500
[Guest]: specific. It says you should not be accepting money or anything of value from a foreign government.

00:44:14.540 --> 00:44:20.700
[Guest]: Right. But foreign government is pretty broadly defined, right? Like it's, it's also agents and

00:44:20.700 --> 00:44:26.540
[Guest]: representatives of a foreign government, counters from a foreign government. Things of value is

00:44:26.540 --> 00:44:31.900
[Guest]: also fairly widely defined. It's not literal money. There can be various things that would be

00:44:31.900 --> 00:44:38.220
[Guest]: useful. This is why there are like protocol vetted and approved gifts for state functions, right.

00:44:38.780 --> 00:44:44.460
[Guest]: And this is why any senior like an ambassador or whoever or whatever, if they receive anything,

00:44:44.460 --> 00:44:48.860
[Guest]: they have to like report the gifts that they get. If it's above a certain value, then it's actually,

00:44:49.660 --> 00:44:54.620
[Guest]: I mean, confiscated is too harsh a word, right? They voluntarily surrender it. And it's either

00:44:54.620 --> 00:45:00.700
[Guest]: like given to a museum or something, or it's put into this big auction and the proceeds are used

00:45:00.700 --> 00:45:05.420
[Guest]: towards, you know, whatever, like a widows and orphans fund or something. Trump owns multiple

00:45:05.420 --> 00:45:11.980
[Guest]: commercial properties around the country. Around the world. He actively promotes them. The

00:45:12.540 --> 00:45:17.820
[Guest]: shining example is the Trump International Hotel in Washington, DC, which was renovated and

00:45:17.820 --> 00:45:21.980
[Guest]: reopened right about when he became president, and which has been booked out by foreign governments

00:45:21.980 --> 00:45:28.460
[Guest]: ever since. Right. And of course, this is money going into the president's pocket. Of course,

00:45:28.460 --> 00:45:32.540
[Guest]: people are like booking large venues and like keeping it booked into like stay in his good

00:45:32.540 --> 00:45:39.180
[Guest]: books. He has golf courses around the country. He has whatever that holiday resort is in Florida

00:45:39.180 --> 00:45:43.100
[Guest]: that he keeps escaping to as well. The name escapes me for a second. But where like they

00:45:43.100 --> 00:45:47.580
[Guest]: were actively like they hiked up membership fees after he became president. They were selling

00:45:47.580 --> 00:45:53.020
[Guest]: spots at like an adjacent table to him at like the holiday party or stuff. When I say he does

00:45:53.020 --> 00:45:59.260
[Amit Varma]: it in a really crass way, I pay a premium for that seat. Though I don't have any money, but if I did,

00:45:59.260 --> 00:46:07.260
[Guest]: I would. I mean, I would pay a premium for it. And then like, you know, install like that bloated

00:46:07.260 --> 00:46:14.060
[Guest]: Trump baby blimp there or something maybe. But it's just really, really obvious that he has

00:46:14.060 --> 00:46:22.060
[Guest]: commercial interests that are benefiting from his being president. The norm, but not the law

00:46:22.060 --> 00:46:27.500
[Guest]: that previous presidents have followed, is to either divest their assets or put them under a

00:46:27.500 --> 00:46:35.100
[Guest]: blind trust. Right. Right. The point of the blind trust, of course, is then you don't know what that

00:46:35.100 --> 00:46:39.980
[Guest]: person is doing and you don't know how the policies that you're working on might affect those

00:46:39.980 --> 00:46:45.420
[Guest]: outcomes. Right. Jimmy Carter famously had to sell his peanut farm before he became president.

00:46:45.420 --> 00:46:46.700
[Amit Varma]: Hopefully not for peanuts.

00:46:46.700 --> 00:46:54.860
[Guest]: And Trump has refused to do this. And it's a norm and not a law. And so every time he's sort of

00:46:54.860 --> 00:47:00.540
[Guest]: like, but there's nothing that says I have to do it. Technically, he's right. Right. But starting

00:47:00.540 --> 00:47:05.260
[Guest]: from I mean, that's exactly where the corrosion starts. The second thing you can look at for

00:47:05.260 --> 00:47:10.060
[Guest]: the sort of Trump's domestic corrosion of institutions is the people that he's put in

00:47:10.060 --> 00:47:13.740
[Guest]: charge of different offices in government, different ministries, different departments,

00:47:13.740 --> 00:47:20.460
[Guest]: different secretaries. Betsy DeVos, who's his education secretary, has massive commercial

00:47:20.460 --> 00:47:26.300
[Guest]: interests in charter schooling. Right. Of course, the way that he argues is that she is a prominent

00:47:26.300 --> 00:47:31.740
[Guest]: educationist. So, of course, she would know. Right. But you are putting the person whose

00:47:31.740 --> 00:47:38.060
[Guest]: entire business model is dependent upon students leaving public schools and going to charter schools

00:47:38.060 --> 00:47:43.980
[Guest]: in charge of public schooling. I don't think I need to spell out the rest of that. Right.

00:47:43.980 --> 00:47:51.820
[Guest]: His secretary of the interior, I think, a guy called Ryan Zinke, is the subject of I don't even

00:47:51.820 --> 00:47:58.700
[Guest]: know how many like ethics and misbehavior investigations. It's like in double digits and like

00:47:58.700 --> 00:48:03.900
[Guest]: 40 plus or something at last count. And remember, they've been in power for less than two years.

00:48:03.900 --> 00:48:08.860
[Guest]: Right. So these are all things that either he's done or that have come to light in the period of

00:48:08.860 --> 00:48:15.340
[Guest]: like the last 18 months or something, which is like, you know, a new infraction every other week.

00:48:16.460 --> 00:48:20.700
[Amit Varma]: So we kind of look at this and we say that, okay, you know, he's running roughshod over all

00:48:20.700 --> 00:48:26.060
[Amit Varma]: these rules, but they apply to the executive branch. And surely the other institutions in

00:48:26.060 --> 00:48:33.500
[Amit Varma]: the US government will prevent too much damage from happening. In theory, yes. It could still

00:48:33.500 --> 00:48:38.540
[Guest]: happen. Right. I mean, Zinke, for instance, I said he faces investigations. Right. Sure. Yes,

00:48:38.540 --> 00:48:44.380
[Guest]: he is being investigated. Part of the problem is that by the time they stopped, some of the

00:48:44.380 --> 00:48:49.500
[Guest]: damage is already done. There's no automatic process. That means that because we think that

00:48:49.500 --> 00:48:55.660
[Guest]: the way that you did this was shady, hence, whatever you decided to do is now reversed.

00:48:55.660 --> 00:49:01.580
[Guest]: Right. Again, that would be a normative or a customary way to approach that question.

00:49:01.580 --> 00:49:07.340
[Guest]: But there isn't necessarily a black letter law that makes it that way. People who saw value in

00:49:07.340 --> 00:49:12.380
[Guest]: preserving the institutions would act that way voluntarily to say, no, I want to avoid even the

00:49:12.380 --> 00:49:18.860
[Guest]: appearance that there is a conflict here. Right. Right. Clearly not this group of people. Added

00:49:18.860 --> 00:49:25.180
[Guest]: to that is the fact that politically and electorally, the Republican Party lawmakers

00:49:25.180 --> 00:49:29.900
[Guest]: who currently hold the majority in the upper house and until a couple of weeks ago held the

00:49:29.900 --> 00:49:34.940
[Guest]: majority in the lower house as well, believed that their political success and their political

00:49:34.940 --> 00:49:42.780
[Guest]: survival depended on being seen as sort of sticking close to Trump and not frustrating his agenda.

00:49:42.780 --> 00:49:50.940
[Guest]: The late Senator John McCain famously torpedoed Trump's effort to repeal Obama's healthcare law

00:49:50.940 --> 00:49:56.700
[Guest]: and like got tons of hate mail for it, which is pretty exceptional because the guy is sort of like

00:49:56.700 --> 00:50:02.060
[Guest]: a folk American hero, right? Exactly. Former prisoner of war during the Vietnam War,

00:50:03.100 --> 00:50:09.100
[Amit Varma]: legendary law, like Senator in his own right. You spoke about how there's no Shakespearean drama,

00:50:09.100 --> 00:50:14.460
[Amit Varma]: but I'd say just a fact on how his own people turned on John McCain in the winter of his years

00:50:14.460 --> 00:50:20.700
[Amit Varma]: is a Shakespeare tragedy in itself. King Lear in DC, I guess. Whether or not you agree with that.

00:50:20.700 --> 00:50:24.780
[Guest]: I agree with the guy, that's irrelevant. Yeah, yeah, I'm not, I'm not trying to

00:50:25.900 --> 00:50:32.380
[Guest]: eulogize John McCain as such. I'm just saying he was a politically popular figure. Exactly.

00:50:32.380 --> 00:50:38.060
[Guest]: And fighting Trump on healthcare cost him a lot of that. And a lot of Republicans looked at that

00:50:38.060 --> 00:50:43.500
[Guest]: and said, do I want to be that guy? Right, right. Another senator, Jeff Flake sort of

00:50:44.060 --> 00:50:50.220
[Guest]: started walking that path, but has been quite silent since then and has not actually voted

00:50:50.220 --> 00:50:56.620
[Guest]: against his party on issues where he says Trump is doing the wrong thing. Right. So here is a term

00:50:56.620 --> 00:51:01.580
[Guest]: that I will generally not use because I think it gets abused a lot, but I'm going to use it of Jeff

00:51:01.580 --> 00:51:06.780
[Guest]: Flake. He's virtue signaling. He really is. Because he has the ability to vote differently.

00:51:07.340 --> 00:51:12.780
[Guest]: But he sort of furrows his brow and says, this is a very sad thing. And then he votes for it.

00:51:12.780 --> 00:51:16.540
[Guest]: And he's not even running for re-election. His seat has now been taken over by somebody else.

00:51:16.540 --> 00:51:20.540
[Guest]: Right. Or will be. Sorry, his seat is falling vacant and somebody will be appointed to it in

00:51:20.540 --> 00:51:29.820
[Guest]: the near future. So Congress is a check, iffy, right? With the Democrat Party taking control of

00:51:31.340 --> 00:51:37.420
[Guest]: the lower house may start being more effective as a check. It's possible. The judiciary has been

00:51:37.420 --> 00:51:42.220
[Guest]: being a check in many ways. Absolutely. The problem, so there's a little bit of a tangent,

00:51:42.220 --> 00:51:46.620
[Guest]: right? But if there's listeners who are sort of interested in the comparative legal system

00:51:46.620 --> 00:51:51.500
[Guest]: between India and the US, one of the biggest differences between the US and India when it

00:51:51.500 --> 00:51:56.220
[Guest]: comes to litigation, especially litigation against the government, is that the US has extremely

00:51:56.220 --> 00:52:02.140
[Guest]: strict rules on standing. Standing is who actually has the right to bring a lawsuit.

00:52:02.140 --> 00:52:10.700
[Guest]: Right. So we have phenomenally lack sort of PIL style standing, right? If somebody somewhere is

00:52:10.700 --> 00:52:16.700
[Guest]: harmed, you as a civic minded citizen can sort of approach the court saying, look, somebody is being

00:52:16.700 --> 00:52:22.140
[Guest]: harmed, violation of fundamental rights, please do something. Right. And different judges over

00:52:22.140 --> 00:52:27.180
[Guest]: the years have sort of had their own attitudes towards this. In the US, the rules are a lot

00:52:27.180 --> 00:52:33.740
[Guest]: stricter. You have to typically show that you, the person bringing the suit, are experiencing some

00:52:33.740 --> 00:52:40.460
[Guest]: kind of harm. And it can be even more complicated. You might have to show that, say, for instance,

00:52:40.460 --> 00:52:44.140
[Guest]: you're not actually a national of the country, you might have to show that even though you're

00:52:44.140 --> 00:52:48.620
[Guest]: not a national, you actually have the right to approach that forum because the nature of the

00:52:48.620 --> 00:52:52.940
[Guest]: harm that you're facing offends the right that is not guaranteed just to nationals or just to

00:52:52.940 --> 00:52:57.020
[Guest]: citizens. It's guaranteed to like all people who happen to be within the territory of the country

00:52:57.020 --> 00:53:01.340
[Guest]: or something. So you could bring a freedom of speech action even as a non-citizen, because

00:53:01.340 --> 00:53:05.660
[Guest]: that's not limited to citizens. It's guaranteed to everybody in the country. You might not be

00:53:05.660 --> 00:53:10.380
[Guest]: able to bring a right to bear arms action. Right. And so suing the federal government in the United

00:53:10.380 --> 00:53:16.860
[Guest]: States is actually a lot harder than suing the central government in India. That said, a number

00:53:16.860 --> 00:53:23.420
[Guest]: of Trump's policies have landed up in court. Right. He revoked a reporter's press pass a couple of

00:53:23.420 --> 00:53:28.460
[Amit Varma]: what last week? Yeah, something like that. Yeah, we're recording this on November 20. By the way,

00:53:28.460 --> 00:53:34.300
[Amit Varma]: the CNN guy Costa, I think is right. CNN went to court. And interestingly, Fox stood by CNN

00:53:34.300 --> 00:53:40.460
[Guest]: in that which was refreshing. Yeah, no, I think the entire White House Correspondents Association

00:53:40.460 --> 00:53:47.980
[Guest]: was like, wait, you can revoke a pass for people being rude to the president? Like,

00:53:48.700 --> 00:53:53.020
[Guest]: none of us is going to get to get in here eventually. Right. And the court stayed it.

00:53:53.020 --> 00:53:57.340
[Guest]: It's a stay. It's not a final ruling. It's an interim ruling. But generally speaking,

00:53:57.340 --> 00:54:02.300
[Guest]: in matters like this, if you can win the interim relief, you have a pretty good shot of winning

00:54:02.300 --> 00:54:06.140
[Guest]: the final thing as well. Right. Because the basis for winning the interim thing is that you were

00:54:06.140 --> 00:54:10.940
[Guest]: experiencing harm while that thing was in effect. And so it needs to be stopped.

00:54:10.940 --> 00:54:14.460
[Guest]: If the judges basically already conceded that you're probably facing harm,

00:54:15.020 --> 00:54:19.580
[Guest]: yeah, it's likely to be reversed. A bunch of executive orders he signed around

00:54:21.580 --> 00:54:27.340
[Guest]: immigration and deportations, famously the bans that he wanted to sign. All of these things were

00:54:27.340 --> 00:54:32.780
[Amit Varma]: challenged successfully in court, which is therefore sort of a sign of hope that, you know,

00:54:32.780 --> 00:54:38.140
[Amit Varma]: the rules and institutions are working. Would you would you say that? Yes. Or you'd qualify it.

00:54:40.620 --> 00:54:44.780
[Guest]: I mean, so this is why I really like that we started with like the game theory of this and

00:54:44.780 --> 00:54:50.620
[Guest]: like the evolution of cooperation in this, right? There are the formal institutions and the formal

00:54:50.620 --> 00:54:56.140
[Guest]: laws. And they will, to some extent, jealously guard their powers and their remits and like

00:54:56.140 --> 00:55:01.580
[Guest]: see to their enforcement. But then surrounding all of that are these entire sets of norms and

00:55:01.580 --> 00:55:09.180
[Guest]: customs and beliefs that if left to run in a positive feedback cycle, start guiding people

00:55:09.180 --> 00:55:14.220
[Guest]: towards greater trust and greater cooperation. That stuff is being damaged. That stuff is being

00:55:14.220 --> 00:55:19.980
[Guest]: harmed. It is being reversed. You know, again, let me not be so sort of ahistorical as to put the

00:55:19.980 --> 00:55:26.620
[Guest]: blame or to put all of the blame on Trump, right? But as the guy in power who is constantly sending

00:55:26.620 --> 00:55:30.380
[Guest]: out the message saying the institutions don't matter, the rules don't matter, what I want matters,

00:55:31.180 --> 00:55:38.860
[Guest]: that's I think doing sort of a, it's doing a degree of harm that is not necessarily visible now,

00:55:38.860 --> 00:55:43.180
[Guest]: but that is actually going to outlast his presidency by a long time. So that's what

00:55:43.180 --> 00:55:47.260
[Amit Varma]: my question is about. I mean, there's one view of Trump that look, this is an accident of history.

00:55:47.260 --> 00:55:51.660
[Amit Varma]: It's an outlier. Here's one mad guy who's gotten to the presidency. But hey, the rules and

00:55:51.660 --> 00:55:55.900
[Amit Varma]: institutions are robust and we'll outlast this and we'll have a sensible president next time,

00:55:55.900 --> 00:56:00.940
[Amit Varma]: or at least a time after that, and things will be back to normal and there'll be no lasting damage.

00:56:00.940 --> 00:56:06.620
[Amit Varma]: But your point is that there can be lasting damage out of all this, all of this man shenanigans,

00:56:06.620 --> 00:56:10.140
[Amit Varma]: which would indicate that the rules and institutions weren't strong enough to begin with.

00:56:10.700 --> 00:56:15.580
[Guest]: I mean, if you Yeah, sure. Like I'll sign on to that. Yeah, they weren't nearly as strong as we

00:56:15.580 --> 00:56:20.460
[Guest]: like to imagine they are. They look strong when like somebody who already believes in them is

00:56:20.460 --> 00:56:25.660
[Amit Varma]: operating them. So what is the lasting damage? Is it a lasting damage to for example, the norms that

00:56:25.660 --> 00:56:30.700
[Amit Varma]: govern conflict of interest and you can't do anything with personal profit or is a greater

00:56:30.700 --> 00:56:35.820
[Guest]: damage than that? So it's hard for me to answer that question, basically, because it depends on

00:56:35.820 --> 00:56:40.780
[Guest]: what us lawmakers do next, right? Right. US lawmakers can say, Hey, we used to have all

00:56:40.780 --> 00:56:44.060
[Guest]: these norms. And we were happy with their functioning because people are bided by them.

00:56:44.060 --> 00:56:49.580
[Guest]: And then we elected a guy who's been destruction testing them. And now that he's actually breached

00:56:49.580 --> 00:56:53.500
[Guest]: a bunch of them, we're going to reinforce them, we're actually going to turn them into laws.

00:56:54.060 --> 00:57:01.660
[Guest]: Right. In which case, the potential damage will be greatly mitigated. But if they don't,

00:57:02.460 --> 00:57:07.260
[Guest]: right, the next chap who finds himself in that situation, and for some completely unrelated

00:57:07.260 --> 00:57:11.580
[Guest]: reason decides, it's going to be embarrassing for me to release my tax returns.

00:57:11.580 --> 00:57:15.020
[Guest]: And there's a precedent for not doing so suddenly,

00:57:15.020 --> 00:57:20.460
[Guest]: you know, no longer has to lift this great burden of being the first person to do so.

00:57:20.460 --> 00:57:25.020
[Amit Varma]: And what Trump has also done is in a manner of speaking, he's already caused lasting damage,

00:57:25.020 --> 00:57:29.100
[Amit Varma]: not specifically to the US, we can't say that yet to the institutions and rules,

00:57:29.100 --> 00:57:32.940
[Amit Varma]: but he's demolished the Republican Party, the Republican Party today

00:57:32.940 --> 00:57:39.260
[Amit Varma]: is a different beast from what it was the way I see it. And that morally corrosive effect

00:57:39.260 --> 00:57:44.220
[Amit Varma]: that power can have on one person has in a manner of speaking spread through the party.

00:57:44.780 --> 00:57:50.460
[Guest]: Yeah, I, again, it's a very chicken and egg question, right around sort of

00:57:51.420 --> 00:57:59.420
[Guest]: who started turning more extreme first, right? There's a book by...

00:58:00.540 --> 00:58:04.940
[Amit Varma]: And there are really three parties here. It's not as if who between Trump and the Republican Party

00:58:04.940 --> 00:58:09.900
[Amit Varma]: is between who between Trump, the Republican Party, and the voter base that they traditionally

00:58:10.460 --> 00:58:11.260
[Amit Varma]: appeal to.

00:58:11.260 --> 00:58:16.700
[Guest]: Right. And yeah, I mean, look, the question gets broader and broader every time we take a stab at

00:58:16.700 --> 00:58:21.900
[Guest]: it, right? Like, oh, there are actually 17 parties. No, the core point is just that.

00:58:23.260 --> 00:58:27.820
[Guest]: How do I say this? Bad behavior gives permission for future bad behavior.

00:58:27.820 --> 00:58:29.180
[Guest]: Yeah. Yeah.

00:58:29.180 --> 00:58:30.460
[Guest]: That's the lasting damage.

00:58:31.180 --> 00:58:33.180
[Amit Varma]: And that's a vicious cycle. I mean,

00:58:33.180 --> 00:58:37.100
[Guest]: Absolutely. Well, and the things that are most vulnerable to it are precisely the things that

00:58:37.100 --> 00:58:40.140
[Guest]: are not actually written up into formal law.

00:58:40.140 --> 00:58:46.540
[Amit Varma]: And the benchmarks go lower and lower. So I can easily see, you know, if the future president

00:58:46.540 --> 00:58:52.380
[Amit Varma]: from the Democratic Party can easily resort to whataboutery anytime he's questioned and say,

00:58:52.380 --> 00:58:58.060
[Amit Varma]: but hey, look what that guy did. And the benchmarks have then just come down a long way.

00:58:58.060 --> 00:59:03.740
[Guest]: So this is a live debate within the Democratic Party this instant, right? And, you know, a number

00:59:03.740 --> 00:59:10.140
[Guest]: of my friends who are about our age, so they're not necessarily active in terms of being

00:59:10.140 --> 00:59:15.820
[Guest]: representatives, but they are very active in terms of being campaign workers, in terms of being

00:59:15.820 --> 00:59:23.900
[Guest]: staffers, in terms of being fundraisers, in terms of being policy experts. It's a very, very live

00:59:23.900 --> 00:59:29.820
[Guest]: debate about whether the Democratic Party, having gotten a measure of power, should respond to

00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:37.500
[Guest]: Republican or Trump hardball tactics in kind, or whether they should sort of model a different

00:59:37.500 --> 00:59:42.860
[Guest]: kind of behavior. I would say Obama tried this as well for a while, right? He tried to model

00:59:43.580 --> 00:59:51.740
[Guest]: Trump's sort of consensus model of decision making. And at some point, he was just, I think

00:59:51.740 --> 00:59:56.540
[Guest]: he said something to the effect of like, you know, you can't dance without a partner or something

00:59:56.540 --> 01:00:05.580
[Guest]: like that. And at least on a certain set of issues, stopped trying. So yeah, one possible outcome

01:00:06.140 --> 01:00:13.500
[Guest]: is that all like the general nature of politics in the United States becomes coarser and more

01:00:13.500 --> 01:00:19.500
[Guest]: divisive and more aligned to groups and more aligned to what some theorists, although again,

01:00:19.500 --> 01:00:24.460
[Guest]: I disagree with this characterization, but what some theorists will describe as identity politics,

01:00:25.100 --> 01:00:30.700
[Guest]: it's possible, because it's the classic, it's the domestic political equivalent of the security

01:00:30.700 --> 01:00:37.180
[Guest]: dilemma, right? You chose to escalate one step more, I can either escalate to match you,

01:00:38.060 --> 01:00:43.180
[Guest]: or I can put my faith in the existing rules and institutions to prevent you from getting away

01:00:43.180 --> 01:00:47.820
[Guest]: with it. And that could take me further behind. And in the short term, that's almost guaranteed

01:00:47.820 --> 01:00:54.140
[Guest]: to put me further behind. Right? And this is a dilemma. If you abide by the rules, while somebody

01:00:54.140 --> 01:01:01.500
[Guest]: else is undermining them, you can be modeling good rule abiding behavior, you can also be losing so

01:01:01.500 --> 01:01:05.660
[Guest]: much power that then the other person is able to completely ignore the rules at some point of time.

01:01:05.660 --> 01:01:11.340
[Guest]: And, you know, thankfully, it's not my job to decide where that is.

01:01:11.340 --> 01:01:15.420
[Amit Varma]: This is in a sense a classic game theory problem. What do you do? Do you take that step back now to

01:01:15.420 --> 01:01:19.420
[Amit Varma]: take the high moral ground? Or do you say I got to play as dirty as the other guy?

01:01:20.140 --> 01:01:21.580
[Amit Varma]: Fuck the rules and the institutions.

01:01:22.460 --> 01:01:29.180
[Guest]: I mean, again, I think that the smart strategy for the Democratic Party, at least to do,

01:01:29.900 --> 01:01:34.460
[Guest]: is to say we're going to play by the rules. But that also means that we're going to crack down

01:01:34.460 --> 01:01:39.180
[Guest]: pretty hard on people who are messing with the rules. Right? It's a hardball strategy of its own.

01:01:40.380 --> 01:01:44.140
[Guest]: But it's not hardball on the same field or on the same arena as the Republicans.

01:01:44.140 --> 01:01:49.660
[Guest]: Yeah. Right. You don't necessarily respond to the same sort of provocations on issues of

01:01:49.660 --> 01:01:56.380
[Guest]: identity or race. You do have your own set of things that you want to hit. And again, this is

01:01:56.380 --> 01:01:59.740
[Guest]: I'm sure I'm not saying anything that's not in like some Democratic politician's

01:01:59.740 --> 01:02:06.300
[Guest]: script book or playbook already. Yeah. Right. But yeah, I mean, I think that even with that

01:02:06.300 --> 01:02:15.340
[Guest]: strategy taken, even then, there is something being I'm not familiar enough with the history

01:02:15.340 --> 01:02:22.780
[Guest]: of US politics to say whether the Republican or Democratic Party shared sort of a history of

01:02:22.780 --> 01:02:27.820
[Guest]: working together on progressive causes. Right. I know they did on like certain sort of pure

01:02:27.820 --> 01:02:31.900
[Guest]: economic causes. But if at all, they did, or if there was the potential for such a thing,

01:02:31.900 --> 01:02:35.740
[Amit Varma]: I think it's largely gone now. It's pretty much gone. And in a sense,

01:02:35.740 --> 01:02:40.380
[Amit Varma]: I think the opposition in India faces the same dilemma when it comes to Modi that do we take the

01:02:40.380 --> 01:02:47.100
[Amit Varma]: high moral ground or do we get as down and dirty as him and it's something I lament constantly that

01:02:47.100 --> 01:02:51.980
[Amit Varma]: the Congress in fact has completely rejected the high moral ground and you know, on social media,

01:02:51.980 --> 01:02:57.340
[Amit Varma]: for example, their IT cell is as vicious and bad as a BJP IT cell in many ways. I mean, I've been

01:02:57.340 --> 01:03:03.340
[Amit Varma]: targeted by both. And, you know, even the kind of soft Hindutva which they are going for and the

01:03:03.340 --> 01:03:07.340
[Amit Varma]: identity politics they're playing, which is, I mean, of course, in India is ubiquitous. And

01:03:07.340 --> 01:03:13.340
[Amit Varma]: I disagree with you and say that even in the US, I think identity politics is a massive growing

01:03:13.340 --> 01:03:18.060
[Amit Varma]: problem. But leaving that sort of aside before we move on to the international arena and what Trump

01:03:18.060 --> 01:03:25.260
[Amit Varma]: is doing there. If I had to ask you to say, outline within the domestic arena, a worst case

01:03:25.260 --> 01:03:29.900
[Amit Varma]: scenario and a best case scenario for how the country will look say, two elections from now,

01:03:29.900 --> 01:03:38.780
[Amit Varma]: let's say into, you know, 2028. You know, what would your worst case and your best case be?

01:03:39.740 --> 01:03:45.420
[Guest]: The worst case is easy. The worst case is that Trump has already won re-election for a second

01:03:45.420 --> 01:03:52.060
[Guest]: term and flouts the Constitution to stand for a third. Right? And at that point of time,

01:03:52.060 --> 01:03:57.500
[Guest]: the institutions are undermined to the extent that he makes Ivanka vice president and then

01:03:57.500 --> 01:04:04.780
[Guest]: dies and she becomes president. I mean, it's, you know, choose your specific nightmare ending,

01:04:04.780 --> 01:04:11.260
[Guest]: right? I think that's pretty far fetched. Right? I think that like, a full blown constitutional

01:04:11.260 --> 01:04:16.540
[Guest]: crisis is not likely to happen. Because there are not actually that many people who are willing to

01:04:16.540 --> 01:04:21.580
[Guest]: serve like the personality cult of Trump. But if it happened, then we'd have to like strike out the

01:04:21.580 --> 01:04:28.540
[Guest]: wannabe, right? Like then he would be genuine autocrat, genuine sort of, you know, Central Asian

01:04:28.540 --> 01:04:35.340
[Guest]: or like Georgian head of state or something like between crime and government and business.

01:04:35.900 --> 01:04:41.020
[Guest]: There's very blurry lines. That would definitely be the worst case because again, this is like the

01:04:41.020 --> 01:04:45.660
[Guest]: country that sort of stands as a historical example of like, we can build honest politics

01:04:45.660 --> 01:04:51.660
[Guest]: out of a criminal past. New York politics used to be criminal in every sense of the word, right?

01:04:51.660 --> 01:04:56.620
[Guest]: Chicago politics used to be criminal in every sense of the word. They've built something better

01:04:56.620 --> 01:05:06.220
[Guest]: out of it. So it would be very sad to see it regress. Best case scenario is that he loses in

01:05:06.220 --> 01:05:13.100
[Guest]: the next election. And I don't care about graciously but concedes defeat. Doesn't sort of

01:05:13.100 --> 01:05:18.220
[Guest]: raise this entire stink around like questing the legitimacy of it. And then one election later is

01:05:18.220 --> 01:05:23.900
[Guest]: a non-issue in whatever is being campaigned, right? Like it's almost, you know, irrespective

01:05:23.900 --> 01:05:28.700
[Guest]: of what sort of codifying of norms actually happens in between or not. By the time it's

01:05:28.700 --> 01:05:33.260
[Guest]: time for whoever's Trump's successor is to stand for re-election, the debate is about them.

01:05:33.260 --> 01:05:34.060
[Guest]: 05.05 Right.

01:05:34.060 --> 01:05:40.860
[Guest]: 05.05 They're not able to use the plank of like, would you rather have Trump in the election then?

01:05:40.860 --> 01:05:44.860
[Guest]: I don't have the information to sort of put a probability estimate on this.

01:05:44.860 --> 01:05:45.660
[Guest]: 05.05 Yeah, yeah.

01:05:45.660 --> 01:05:50.780
[Guest]: 05.05 It's just sort of, this is what I would like to see happen is continuing with democratic

01:05:50.780 --> 01:05:58.140
[Guest]: transitions of power. And basically, whatever Trumpism is, it's sort of shoved out of the

01:05:58.140 --> 01:06:01.100
[Guest]: marketplace of ideas by better, more compelling things.

01:06:01.100 --> 01:06:06.140
[Amit Varma]: 05.15 One would hope so. And now moving on to the, you know, the international domain,

01:06:06.140 --> 01:06:10.140
[Amit Varma]: and there is kind of more worrying because in the US, you have all these checks and balances,

01:06:10.140 --> 01:06:17.020
[Amit Varma]: like you said, you have a strong judiciary, which has acted at times as an effective check on him.

01:06:17.020 --> 01:06:20.300
[Amit Varma]: 05.30 You have all of that happening. I mean, despite the erosion of norms,

01:06:20.300 --> 01:06:24.780
[Amit Varma]: institutions are still kind of standing up to some extent. But internationally,

01:06:24.780 --> 01:06:29.820
[Amit Varma]: there really aren't that many checks and balances. The US is a huge superpower with huge clout and

01:06:29.820 --> 01:06:35.660
[Amit Varma]: every decision that Trump makes, especially with those regarding trade, for example,

01:06:35.660 --> 01:06:37.420
[Amit Varma]: affect billions of people, literally.

01:06:37.420 --> 01:06:44.860
[Guest]: 05.40 Yeah, so this is where it's hard to find a silver lining, right? The international system

01:06:44.860 --> 01:06:50.860
[Guest]: or the international order as we know it in its current form, is only about 70-75 years old.

01:06:52.300 --> 01:06:58.620
[Guest]: UN was formed right after World War Two. And the sort of, in that period of time,

01:06:58.620 --> 01:07:05.020
[Guest]: it has not been able to develop to the extent that there are strong institutions or independently

01:07:05.020 --> 01:07:11.900
[Guest]: enforced rules. There is a field called international law. But there are also people,

01:07:12.700 --> 01:07:17.820
[Guest]: notably in the United States and in law schools in the United States, who will even now write

01:07:17.820 --> 01:07:21.260
[Guest]: articles arguing that there is actually no such thing called international law,

01:07:21.260 --> 01:07:22.780
[Guest]: because there is nobody who can enforce it.

01:07:22.780 --> 01:07:24.940
[Guest]: 06.00 And your response to that would be?

01:07:24.940 --> 01:07:30.620
[Guest]: 06.00 Just because it doesn't look like domestic law doesn't necessarily mean that it's not law.

01:07:30.620 --> 01:07:36.380
[Guest]: 06.00 Right. And equally, as somebody who's trained as a lawyer, I promise you that both

01:07:36.380 --> 01:07:40.060
[Guest]: enforcement issues and variation are very much a part of domestic law as well.

01:07:40.060 --> 01:07:40.700
[Guest]: 06.00 Right.

01:07:40.700 --> 01:07:44.780
[Guest]: 06.00 Right. The last thing that a lawyer will find convincing is if you say, but it's the law.

01:07:44.780 --> 01:07:45.500
[Guest]: 06.00 Right.

01:07:45.500 --> 01:07:48.460
[Guest]: 06.00 They're like, yeah, that's my job. They're like, that's where my job starts.

01:07:49.020 --> 01:07:54.060
[Guest]: Right. But because there isn't necessarily like an overarching institution to sort of be the

01:07:54.060 --> 01:08:01.260
[Guest]: 06.00 guarantor of the rules, or to punish bad behaviour, international law is still very much a

01:08:01.260 --> 01:08:08.060
[Guest]: system that largely follows the wishes of the most powerful, and military and financially is the

01:08:08.060 --> 01:08:14.140
[Guest]: United States. And so this is why Trump is just this grand experiment, right? And I say that

01:08:14.140 --> 01:08:18.620
[Guest]: because I don't want to say anything more despairing. You've taken someone who is

01:08:19.740 --> 01:08:23.180
[Guest]: fundamentally opposed to the principles of the international system.

01:08:23.180 --> 01:08:28.780
[Guest]: 06.00 Right, who's opposed to the idea of long term cooperation, who's opposed to the idea of

01:08:28.780 --> 01:08:34.620
[Guest]: treating states as equals, who is opposed to the idea of any sort of constraint on the power of

01:08:34.620 --> 01:08:40.700
[Amit Varma]: the powerful, and who sees the world fundamentally in a zero sum way. And you know, where everything

01:08:40.700 --> 01:08:46.140
[Amit Varma]: is transactional. And if you win, I must be losing and you know, doesn't understand the

01:08:46.140 --> 01:08:52.060
[Guest]: positive sumness of international relations. Absolutely. Well, so Trump is like, he's truly

01:08:52.060 --> 01:08:57.180
[Guest]: the worst kind of like zero sum theorist, right? Like, he's a megalomaniac simpleton.

01:08:57.180 --> 01:09:00.460
[Guest]: He's a zero sum theorist with the ability to flip over the gaming table.

01:09:02.540 --> 01:09:06.620
[Guest]: You know, he's the, I'm out, so I have a bat, I'm taking it.

01:09:06.620 --> 01:09:16.620
[Guest]: Exactly. And that's incredibly scary. Because in this case, he really has the ability

01:09:16.620 --> 01:09:24.780
[Guest]: to like ruin the game by walking away or by like, as seems more likely, you know,

01:09:24.780 --> 01:09:32.860
[Guest]: using it as a weapon as opposed to a sporting implement. So the post World War International

01:09:32.860 --> 01:09:42.940
[Guest]: Order was built upon largely the willingness and the impetus and the enlightened self interest of

01:09:42.940 --> 01:09:49.820
[Guest]: successive US government leaders. Right? This is not to detract the role that literally everybody

01:09:49.820 --> 01:09:55.340
[Guest]: else in the world has played. But to say that the fact that the US was willing to play along was a

01:09:55.340 --> 01:09:59.740
[Guest]: necessary condition. Only then were we in a place where it was conducive for these things to

01:09:59.740 --> 01:10:05.180
[Guest]: develop. And like Trump's inaugural speech was from now on, it will be America first.

01:10:05.180 --> 01:10:14.940
[Guest]: Right. Right. And his, you know, his national security advisor is literally the most famous,

01:10:15.580 --> 01:10:22.220
[Guest]: most vehement anti international law American diplomat that there is John Bolton of the

01:10:22.220 --> 01:10:28.620
[Guest]: flamboyant mustache, who in his in his time as the US ambassador to the United Nations was

01:10:28.620 --> 01:10:32.380
[Amit Varma]: the most hated man in that building. In Bush's time, he was one of Bush's

01:10:32.380 --> 01:10:37.500
[Guest]: most hated operatives, which is saying a lot. So he was I mean, he was hated by his own colleagues

01:10:37.500 --> 01:10:43.340
[Guest]: in the White House, right. And he was hated by diplomats in the UN. It says something to his

01:10:43.340 --> 01:10:48.620
[Guest]: skills as like a bureaucrat and a maneuverer, that he was able to actually keep his position

01:10:48.620 --> 01:10:53.340
[Guest]: for that long. And by the way, he's one of those few people that I have not heard accused of,

01:10:54.060 --> 01:10:58.860
[Guest]: like, crime or dirty dealings. Right, right. It's there's there's no argument made that the

01:10:58.860 --> 01:11:12.700
[Guest]: man is corrupt. Right, like Modi. Bolton genuinely believes that like, anything that detracts from

01:11:12.700 --> 01:11:17.740
[Guest]: the sovereignty of the United States is the equivalent of like an attack on the United States.

01:11:17.740 --> 01:11:22.860
[Guest]: And he firmly believes that any treaty automatically detracts from the sovereignty of the United

01:11:22.860 --> 01:11:27.180
[Guest]: States. And so you have you have like the guy who's saying from now on, it will be America first.

01:11:27.180 --> 01:11:34.140
[Guest]: And the guy who's saying treaties are an unacceptable infringement on one team with

01:11:34.140 --> 01:11:38.380
[Guest]: the power to do the things that they want to do. And it's a complete misunderstanding of America

01:11:38.380 --> 01:11:43.180
[Amit Varma]: first, because America first really means you can only be first through cooperation,

01:11:43.180 --> 01:11:47.740
[Amit Varma]: everybody benefits at the same time. And this will actually take America backwards what he's doing.

01:11:47.740 --> 01:11:51.660
[Amit Varma]: But the greater problem is it'll take the rest of the world backwards as well. Absolutely. I mean,

01:11:51.660 --> 01:11:55.740
[Guest]: this is exactly what Macron said, right. By the way, there is a history to that slogan as well.

01:11:55.740 --> 01:12:01.980
[Guest]: To America first. That history relates to sort of like the proto fascist movement within the US

01:12:01.980 --> 01:12:09.980
[Guest]: itself. And so it's not like Trump took like an innocent idea and sort of cast his own view on it.

01:12:10.860 --> 01:12:17.900
[Guest]: By design or accident, I suspect accident, he tapped into exactly the vein of things that he

01:12:17.900 --> 01:12:23.740
[Amit Varma]: wanted to tap into. Both Occam's razor and Hanlon's razor, I'd say probably by accident,

01:12:23.740 --> 01:12:29.020
[Amit Varma]: I never ascribe to malice, but you can ascribe to stupidity and he is a simpleton.

01:12:29.020 --> 01:12:35.900
[Guest]: But in his case, he's stupid and malignant. And so it's over determined. This was Ben Wittes,

01:12:35.900 --> 01:12:42.700
[Guest]: I think, of lawfare on Twitter at some point of time was like, the only thing that tempers

01:12:42.700 --> 01:12:48.140
[Guest]: this administration's malignance is its incompetence. Like it's the living version

01:12:48.140 --> 01:12:52.140
[Guest]: of sort of like, would you rather have like a bumbling well intentioned person? Sorry,

01:12:52.140 --> 01:12:56.700
[Guest]: would you rather have like an ill intentioned bumbling person or like an effective ill intentioned

01:12:56.700 --> 01:13:04.140
[Guest]: person? You've got the bumbling ill intentioned person. But I mean, just look at like the list of

01:13:04.140 --> 01:13:09.580
[Guest]: treaties that this administration and again, they've been here less than two years. Right.

01:13:09.580 --> 01:13:15.180
[Guest]: So this is quite the piece. I was trying to like, total these up on my phone on the way in right.

01:13:15.820 --> 01:13:21.820
[Guest]: The Paris Agreement on climate change, literally the only country left out or like one of two

01:13:21.820 --> 01:13:26.540
[Guest]: countries left out at this point. I forget which the other country was, but their argument was that

01:13:26.540 --> 01:13:32.460
[Guest]: Paris was not stringent enough, which is why they were not signing the Trans Pacific Partnership.

01:13:33.340 --> 01:13:36.700
[Guest]: Right, which was basically going to be the biggest trade agreement in the world.

01:13:36.700 --> 01:13:37.260
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:13:37.260 --> 01:13:43.980
[Guest]: Right. And whose entire purpose was to contain China, whose stated goal repeatedly stated while

01:13:43.980 --> 01:13:47.420
[Guest]: it was being negotiated was we need to have a counterbalance to China on trade,

01:13:47.420 --> 01:13:52.940
[Guest]: which you would think would make it attractive to, but no. Trans Pacific Partnership, NAFTA,

01:13:53.660 --> 01:13:58.780
[Guest]: right, the North American Free Trade Agreement, which is considered sort of like the landmark

01:13:58.780 --> 01:14:03.180
[Guest]: free trade agreement for, and not to say that NAFTA didn't have negative effects, but for the

01:14:03.180 --> 01:14:07.500
[Guest]: most part, those negative effects were exported to Mexico and Canada. They weren't showing up in

01:14:07.500 --> 01:14:12.940
[Guest]: the United States. NAFTA has now been renegotiated. It is a new agreement called the US Mexico Canada

01:14:12.940 --> 01:14:19.660
[Guest]: Agreement, which, you know, you read reporting from when the negotiation was going on. And one

01:14:19.660 --> 01:14:24.860
[Guest]: of the conditions for whatever was supposed to replace NAFTA was that it could not be called

01:14:24.860 --> 01:14:30.620
[Guest]: NAFTA. Like this was a thing that the United States diplomats had instructions to make sure

01:14:30.620 --> 01:14:37.900
[Guest]: happened, right? Which is like, again, it's sort of like simultaneously stupid and like really petty.

01:14:37.900 --> 01:14:43.260
[Guest]: The Korea US agreement was threatened. I think they sort of worked out an arrangement as well.

01:14:43.260 --> 01:14:46.940
[Guest]: But again, this is sort of one of those historic agreements that's been around for like 50,

01:14:46.940 --> 01:14:51.580
[Guest]: 60 years chugging along. Nobody has a problem with it. Trump somewhere in his head, like still

01:14:51.580 --> 01:14:59.980
[Guest]: has a memory of like auto tariff wars or something of like US Japan and US Korea manufacturing wars,

01:14:59.980 --> 01:15:05.660
[Guest]: which is so completely in the past, right? Neither of them is competing in that space anymore,

01:15:05.660 --> 01:15:11.420
[Guest]: really, right? But he threatened it. And he threatened it while there was like a North Korea,

01:15:11.420 --> 01:15:19.180
[Guest]: US South Korea negotiation going on, right? It was just confusing. The universal postal union,

01:15:19.180 --> 01:15:25.100
[Guest]: which is literally like 140 plus year old treaty that just has to do with like, you know, like,

01:15:25.820 --> 01:15:30.620
[Guest]: stamps. Yeah, like it's literally like, I think it's the it's the thing on which the zip code

01:15:30.620 --> 01:15:35.740
[Guest]: system is built. The idea that there will be a numerical code that designates a geographic location.

01:15:36.300 --> 01:15:39.820
[Guest]: And here is like sort of the register of them. And like, here is the system,

01:15:39.820 --> 01:15:43.020
[Guest]: you know, US you get like code starting with these numbers.

01:15:43.020 --> 01:15:45.420
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so something basically no freaking consequence.

01:15:46.780 --> 01:15:53.820
[Guest]: But Trump believes that something in that treaty is allowing China to like, send freight cheaply

01:15:53.820 --> 01:15:58.940
[Guest]: within the United States or whatever. And so he's like, we'll punish them by pulling out of it. And

01:15:58.940 --> 01:16:05.820
[Amit Varma]: like, you know, it's just like most egregiously the trade wars he started with China, which of

01:16:05.820 --> 01:16:10.060
[Amit Varma]: course, if China reciprocates, and you know, the entire world suffers the consequences of that,

01:16:10.060 --> 01:16:15.980
[Guest]: including India, hugely. So I mean, the only reason I haven't put the US China trade war on

01:16:15.980 --> 01:16:20.460
[Guest]: this list is because he hasn't literally like broken a treaty to do it. Yeah, but it's just

01:16:21.260 --> 01:16:26.380
[Guest]: the same thing. Yeah, yeah, no, I and and I'm very sure that the existence of a treaty would

01:16:26.380 --> 01:16:33.420
[Guest]: not have stopped from doing it either. So, you know, yeah, the US China trade war, right, which

01:16:33.420 --> 01:16:41.020
[Guest]: is just like the, I mean, it's sort of basic economics, right? Like comparative advantage

01:16:41.020 --> 01:16:45.100
[Amit Varma]: theory of trade. I mean, I had an episode on this. I mean, just again, it shows his

01:16:45.100 --> 01:16:50.060
[Amit Varma]: zero sum view of the world that he looks as a trade deficit as something that is bad. And no,

01:16:50.060 --> 01:16:54.540
[Amit Varma]: fiscal deficits are bad. Trade deficits are perfectly fine. I mean, I run a trade deficit

01:16:54.540 --> 01:16:58.620
[Amit Varma]: with my domestic help, you know, I pay them every month, they never pay me, it's perfectly fine,

01:16:58.620 --> 01:17:05.500
[Amit Varma]: both parties are benefiting. It's a positive sum game and to sort of impose tariffs and all of that

01:17:05.500 --> 01:17:10.140
[Amit Varma]: not just hurts the Chinese, it hurts your own people. It's crazy. I mean, this is the exact

01:17:10.140 --> 01:17:18.220
[Guest]: illustration of not just zero sum, but also wrong. Yeah, like it's like, you think you're hurting

01:17:18.220 --> 01:17:22.380
[Guest]: China, you're committing a crime on your own people. Indeed, no. And I mean, fundamentally,

01:17:22.380 --> 01:17:28.300
[Guest]: the idea that the way that Trump describes a trade deficit is to say they are taking our money,

01:17:29.340 --> 01:17:36.300
[Guest]: right, which is kind of true, but they're selling you stuff back for it. Like you're getting the

01:17:36.300 --> 01:17:41.020
[Amit Varma]: goods and you're getting value out of that, both parties are benefiting. It's a payment,

01:17:41.020 --> 01:17:46.380
[Guest]: it's not theft. And I mean, can you imagine having a conversation with the head of state

01:17:46.380 --> 01:17:51.260
[Guest]: or you have to explain this? Yeah. Right. Because like, that's what White House staffers actually

01:17:51.260 --> 01:17:57.180
[Guest]: have to do. And clearly, they're not succeeding at it. And, you know, it's unclear if it's because

01:17:57.740 --> 01:18:02.460
[Guest]: the man doesn't get the concept, or it's just too invested in this narrative. But the other

01:18:02.460 --> 01:18:07.420
[Guest]: area also that we have to touch on when we talk about like dismantling treaties and the trade

01:18:07.420 --> 01:18:12.620
[Guest]: wars is in nuclear nonproliferation, right. And so the Iran nuclear deal that he's pulled out of,

01:18:13.500 --> 01:18:19.500
[Guest]: which was sort of the, you know, the landmark achievement of nonproliferation of the past

01:18:19.500 --> 01:18:24.620
[Guest]: decade. I did an episode for this with Pawan on the Pragati podcast before. Trump basically pulled

01:18:24.620 --> 01:18:30.300
[Guest]: out of it on the grounds, not that the deal was not working, but that it was not stopping Iran

01:18:30.300 --> 01:18:34.780
[Guest]: from doing other things that he didn't want them to do. Excellent. Right. Which again, sort of

01:18:34.780 --> 01:18:39.420
[Guest]: negotiation 101 is that you hive off issues. Yeah. And then you reach agreement on things that you

01:18:39.420 --> 01:18:44.620
[Guest]: can and you kick down the road the things that you can't. And then you cooperate on the things

01:18:44.620 --> 01:18:49.260
[Guest]: that you do when the trust builds up. And then you're actually able to re-imagine a solution to

01:18:49.260 --> 01:18:53.100
[Guest]: the things down the road because now you trust each other more. So it's not that you're kicking

01:18:53.100 --> 01:18:56.540
[Guest]: it down the road just because you have nothing better to do at that time. Right. But eventually

01:18:56.540 --> 01:19:01.420
[Amit Varma]: it'll become a non-issue if you keep cooperating. Right. I mean, this is the... So tell me something,

01:19:01.420 --> 01:19:05.740
[Amit Varma]: let's kind of deviate up and perhaps I'm being simplistic here. And if I am, please correct me.

01:19:05.740 --> 01:19:11.340
[Amit Varma]: But let's kind of deviate up into, let's say security implications on the world and economic

01:19:11.340 --> 01:19:16.780
[Amit Varma]: implications on the world. Obviously, the two are related and deeply intertwined. But what is the

01:19:16.780 --> 01:19:21.900
[Amit Varma]: role that global institutions play in each of these domains? And what are the ways in which

01:19:21.900 --> 01:19:27.500
[Guest]: Trump is undermining them? Two big things in security. One, the norm of non-aggression.

01:19:28.060 --> 01:19:33.980
[Guest]: You're not supposed to conquer territory by war. Russia broke this in Ukraine. A very simplistic

01:19:33.980 --> 01:19:40.140
[Guest]: version is that Trump is going amazingly soft on Russia. Right. Again, apply Occam's razor,

01:19:40.140 --> 01:19:46.380
[Guest]: apply Hanlon's razor. A range of explanations emerge. But the fact that territorial aggression

01:19:46.380 --> 01:19:52.300
[Guest]: is not being punished and other countries can consider it hugely destabilizing and damaging.

01:19:52.300 --> 01:19:57.820
[Guest]: Again, not something that we'll see play out immediately, but potentially down the line,

01:19:57.820 --> 01:20:02.220
[Guest]: somebody else who decides that they want to be adventurous has the Russians to point to

01:20:02.220 --> 01:20:08.620
[Guest]: and has the fact that the world sort of acquiesced in that. Right. Or has Trump's actions to point

01:20:08.620 --> 01:20:13.260
[Guest]: to as proof that the world has acquiesced in it, which is not at all a positive development.

01:20:14.300 --> 01:20:21.980
[Guest]: The other is non-proliferation. Right. And non-usage and like steps towards denuclearization,

01:20:22.780 --> 01:20:27.740
[Guest]: independent of any specific thing that's been done. Right. Let's just say this is the very

01:20:27.740 --> 01:20:35.260
[Guest]: last subject on which you want someone who is zero-sum, short-termist and uninformed by science

01:20:35.260 --> 01:20:41.420
[Guest]: to be in charge of things. Right. The potential for disaster is enormous to the extent that actual

01:20:41.420 --> 01:20:47.820
[Guest]: proliferation does continue, which is a very real threat because the North Koreans have shown that

01:20:47.820 --> 01:20:53.740
[Guest]: they are extremely willing to sell nuclear technology. They're an extremely poor country.

01:20:53.740 --> 01:20:57.980
[Guest]: This is one of the most valuable things they can export. If they get the opportunity, they'll try.

01:20:58.620 --> 01:21:02.540
[Guest]: Anybody who's willing to buy nuclear science or material from the North Koreans

01:21:02.540 --> 01:21:07.100
[Guest]: is almost by definition someone who should not be getting their hands on nuclear materials or

01:21:07.100 --> 01:21:11.340
[Guest]: science. And if the US sort of has this blasé attitude towards North Korea of like,

01:21:11.900 --> 01:21:15.900
[Guest]: no, the president and your leader met and like they worked out a deal and they now they have

01:21:15.900 --> 01:21:20.220
[Guest]: a love story or whatever it is, then it's going to be hard to keep track of those things.

01:21:20.780 --> 01:21:27.740
[Guest]: So that's my two for security. Economic, I would split into, I mean, look, whatever we have to say

01:21:27.740 --> 01:21:34.860
[Guest]: about the trade war is still inadequate, right? Like it's just so harmful on so many levels.

01:21:34.860 --> 01:21:38.860
[Amit Varma]: I mean, Trump has turned it literally into a negative sum game where all parties suffer.

01:21:38.860 --> 01:21:44.380
[Guest]: Exactly. Exactly. Yeah. It's not even zero anymore. It's, you know, those, those like

01:21:44.380 --> 01:21:50.300
[Guest]: fantasy novels where like to resolve a duel, each person will like gash themselves with a knife

01:21:51.100 --> 01:21:56.540
[Guest]: and the person who gives up first, like loses the duel or whatever. That's what we're playing now.

01:21:56.540 --> 01:21:59.740
[Amit Varma]: Right. Yeah. I have one limb left, but you have none.

01:22:01.180 --> 01:22:03.580
[Guest]: Monty Python references. I'll bite you. I will.

01:22:05.980 --> 01:22:12.380
[Guest]: Independent of independent of the US China anger, right? I don't know what stance Trump has taken

01:22:12.380 --> 01:22:19.500
[Guest]: on WTO. But I like I find it very easy to believe that the moment something in the WTO goes against

01:22:19.500 --> 01:22:28.780
[Guest]: the US, he'll jump to undermine it as well. And the WTO is the basis of one of the rarest and most

01:22:28.780 --> 01:22:34.460
[Guest]: valuable kinds of things in international law, which is an agreed forum for dispute resolution.

01:22:35.180 --> 01:22:43.100
[Guest]: So if that loses its effect, right, to be fair, the US is a very spotty track record of actually

01:22:43.100 --> 01:22:48.620
[Guest]: complying with WTO rulings and enforcement in the first place. Right. But I mean, this is the

01:22:48.620 --> 01:22:54.380
[Guest]: difference between Obama or some other president saying, I'm going to find a loophole that lets me

01:22:54.380 --> 01:23:00.460
[Guest]: do this, but that keep the optics right. And they'd still be seen as upholding the role or the

01:23:00.460 --> 01:23:07.020
[Guest]: value of the institution. Right. And Trump just sort of being like, they took our money. Yeah,

01:23:07.020 --> 01:23:11.420
[Guest]: they were rude to me and whatever. And so we're not going to, oh, sorry, I actually have to

01:23:11.420 --> 01:23:18.140
[Guest]: backtrack and add one to security. NATO, the fact that he's like, so averse to NATO that he claims

01:23:18.140 --> 01:23:24.220
[Guest]: that NATO is like taking American money so that it doesn't spend on defence, which is not a

01:23:25.020 --> 01:23:29.980
[Guest]: implausible interpretation of the collective defence agreement. It's just that that agreement

01:23:29.980 --> 01:23:35.580
[Guest]: doesn't really mean that European countries have to pay money to the United States, right, to

01:23:36.220 --> 01:23:43.340
[Guest]: loop back to where we started. It's not that kind of protection racket. And Trump had to be cornered

01:23:43.340 --> 01:23:49.260
[Guest]: into saying something that should be just like, like a casual statement for any US president,

01:23:50.060 --> 01:23:57.020
[Guest]: which is, we believe in Article 5 of the NATO treaty, which is the assurance of mutual self

01:23:57.020 --> 01:24:02.540
[Guest]: defence. And he resists it, he fights every time because he doesn't want to say I'm willing to

01:24:02.540 --> 01:24:07.180
[Guest]: come to the defence of, in fact, he says the opposite. He's like, why should I care if like

01:24:07.180 --> 01:24:13.420
[Guest]: X country in Europe is being targeted? Right. And like, of course, it's not about X country. It's

01:24:13.420 --> 01:24:17.820
[Guest]: about the value of the existence of this alliance. And to be fair, he's been very consistent,

01:24:17.820 --> 01:24:22.220
[Amit Varma]: Trump, the president has been consistent to Trump, the campaigner, he used to say pretty

01:24:22.220 --> 01:24:28.300
[Guest]: much the same kind of nonsense on the campaign trail. Right. He did target NATO even while

01:24:28.300 --> 01:24:32.780
[Guest]: campaigning on exactly these grounds. The sad thing is that like he's been corrected multiple

01:24:32.780 --> 01:24:39.580
[Guest]: times on this, right. And again, he's not willing to give up his pet narrative on it. But so on

01:24:39.580 --> 01:24:47.180
[Guest]: economy, China trade war, WTO, migration, right? Like we should not lose track of the fact that

01:24:48.140 --> 01:24:52.780
[Guest]: one of the major ways that global flows happen and that value moves around the world is through

01:24:52.780 --> 01:24:58.700
[Guest]: people. Right. And Trump is clearly trying to build Fortress America that like people cannot

01:24:58.700 --> 01:25:04.140
[Guest]: actually get into that multiple levels, whether that's like asylum and refugee policy, whether

01:25:04.140 --> 01:25:08.940
[Guest]: that's like labor migration, whether it's migration by skilled workers, whatever. And again, if he

01:25:08.940 --> 01:25:13.740
[Guest]: just does it in the United States, arguably, like the people who could have gone to the United

01:25:13.740 --> 01:25:19.180
[Guest]: States lose out, obviously, the United States itself also loses out. The danger is that other

01:25:19.180 --> 01:25:23.660
[Guest]: countries either retaliate or take it as a precedent, right, which is not implausible at all,

01:25:23.660 --> 01:25:27.660
[Guest]: right. When he when he first brought those travel bans, one of the things that he said was these

01:25:27.660 --> 01:25:33.900
[Guest]: will apply even to dual citizens who have one of their citizenships from these countries. But if

01:25:33.900 --> 01:25:41.420
[Guest]: the other citizenship is France or the UK or something, I mean, technically under like the

01:25:41.420 --> 01:25:47.580
[Guest]: letter of the diplomatic relations or the consular relations treaties, these are subjects of

01:25:47.580 --> 01:25:53.500
[Guest]: reciprocity. And if you're not allowing someone who's a French citizen into the country, you know,

01:25:53.500 --> 01:25:58.700
[Guest]: in theory, the French are supposed to like suspend access for US citizens into France.

01:25:59.580 --> 01:26:03.100
[Guest]: Right. The French will obviously make a decision about whether they want to do this or not.

01:26:03.100 --> 01:26:05.740
[Amit Varma]: And they obviously won't because they're not led by a madman yet.

01:26:06.460 --> 01:26:14.300
[Guest]: Right. But you can see this starting to, not that we're at the situation where there really is like

01:26:14.300 --> 01:26:18.940
[Guest]: global free movement of people, but there is at least global regulated movement of people.

01:26:18.940 --> 01:26:19.420
[Guest]: Right.

01:26:19.420 --> 01:26:24.060
[Guest]: And you can see this sort of leading to a situation where like bits of that become islands

01:26:24.060 --> 01:26:25.260
[Guest]: that don't speak to each other.

01:26:25.260 --> 01:26:29.260
[Amit Varma]: Right. And we move backwards, like we're moving backwards on trade, we move backwards on.

01:26:29.260 --> 01:26:32.380
[Guest]: So if we regress on migration as well, then that's another

01:26:33.100 --> 01:26:37.820
[Guest]: vector of the creation of value and global flows that drops.

01:26:38.860 --> 01:26:42.140
[Amit Varma]: So, I mean, I was going to ask you about the worst case scenario and the best case scenario

01:26:42.140 --> 01:26:45.100
[Amit Varma]: in the international domain. But I think the worst case scenario is fairly obvious,

01:26:45.100 --> 01:26:50.380
[Amit Varma]: is nuclear war and we all get wiped out. Are there less worse?

01:26:50.380 --> 01:26:54.540
[Guest]: Oh, so I don't think that interstate nuclear war is actually sort of likely, right?

01:26:56.300 --> 01:26:57.420
[Unknown]: What is your worst case?

01:26:57.420 --> 01:27:02.140
[Guest]: You know, it sort of strains credibility, but I have to, I mean, I have to believe that

01:27:02.860 --> 01:27:07.580
[Guest]: a country that, well, many countries that currently have nuclear weapons,

01:27:08.380 --> 01:27:13.500
[Guest]: arguably even including Russia, might make the enlightened choice to

01:27:13.500 --> 01:27:15.740
[Guest]: absorb a nuclear strike and not retaliate.

01:27:17.100 --> 01:27:21.900
[Guest]: Right? Like, there's again, there's really great game theory work on this on sort of like,

01:27:21.900 --> 01:27:24.940
[Guest]: what is your decision tree like after you've faced the first strike?

01:27:24.940 --> 01:27:30.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but how does sort of game theory take into account an irrational fool like Trump?

01:27:30.380 --> 01:27:36.460
[Guest]: I mean, correct. No, that's why I said many, including even maybe Russia, but not the United.

01:27:36.460 --> 01:27:40.700
[Amit Varma]: So, I mean, I'd say Putin is much more rational than Trump for that matter.

01:27:40.700 --> 01:27:41.820
[Guest]: At least in affairs like this.

01:27:41.820 --> 01:27:43.500
[Guest]: Much more evil, but much more rational.

01:27:43.500 --> 01:27:46.700
[Guest]: Yeah, no, one believes he's the other, right? He's the evil competent one.

01:27:47.420 --> 01:27:52.140
[Guest]: Yeah. No, my worst case in the nuclear space has to do with

01:27:52.140 --> 01:27:57.020
[Guest]: proliferation to like non-state or rogue actors, which I think just like slips under the radar,

01:27:57.020 --> 01:28:00.940
[Guest]: because the US is not doing the same good job of like, global coalition

01:28:00.940 --> 01:28:02.540
[Amit Varma]: building and enforcement that it does.

01:28:02.540 --> 01:28:06.620
[Amit Varma]: So like they set off a dirty nuke in Bombay and you and I are wiped out and the Delhi people

01:28:06.620 --> 01:28:09.180
[Amit Varma]: are laughing and saying, hey, you said our air was polluted.

01:28:09.180 --> 01:28:13.900
[Guest]: That would be terrible. The worst part of that would be the joke. But yes, the joke is terrible.

01:28:15.900 --> 01:28:22.540
[Guest]: Best case again, I think, is that especially European leaders sort of lead a concerted effort

01:28:22.540 --> 01:28:27.420
[Guest]: to say, since we know that these are the kinds of stresses and like variations that we have to deal

01:28:27.420 --> 01:28:33.340
[Guest]: with, let's invest in building sort of more robust, more codified things against this possibility.

01:28:33.340 --> 01:28:36.460
[Guest]: This is sort of not let a good crisis go to waste.

01:28:36.460 --> 01:28:37.020
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:28:37.020 --> 01:28:40.220
[Guest]: And actually improve the robustness of your institutions in the process.

01:28:40.940 --> 01:28:44.700
[Amit Varma]: And sort of to move on from Trump right at the end of this episode,

01:28:45.340 --> 01:28:49.420
[Amit Varma]: you know, Trump isn't an isolated phenomenon in the sense that there are populists all over.

01:28:49.420 --> 01:28:54.860
[Amit Varma]: And we do have a populist authoritarian in power right now in India. But Trump is very

01:28:54.860 --> 01:28:59.260
[Amit Varma]: unusual in the sense that, you know, Narendra Modi at least is a conventional politician who's

01:28:59.260 --> 01:29:03.980
[Amit Varma]: come up in politics for, you know, all those decades. And you could say that in certain ways,

01:29:03.980 --> 01:29:09.100
[Amit Varma]: he's a rational player. He's responding to political incentives and so on. Trump was a

01:29:09.100 --> 01:29:14.940
[Amit Varma]: pure freak of nature who is completely irrational, who doesn't lie as much as he bullshits, to use

01:29:14.940 --> 01:29:22.540
[Amit Varma]: Harry Frank's famous phrasing of it. Is there a threat for you in that, for example, we could

01:29:22.540 --> 01:29:28.540
[Amit Varma]: one day miss Modi, that there could be a leader in charge who is more like Trump, less rational,

01:29:28.540 --> 01:29:34.620
[Amit Varma]: less rational, or more willing to play to whatever extremes seem to work at the moment?

01:29:35.180 --> 01:29:40.300
[Amit Varma]: And I mean, is there a cautionary tale there? Or is there a lesson to be learned about,

01:29:40.300 --> 01:29:44.780
[Amit Varma]: say, India's rules and institutions, and how good they are or how weak they are?

01:29:45.900 --> 01:29:52.060
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely. Not even to single out India, right? Globally, there is a trend of established

01:29:52.060 --> 01:29:57.820
[Guest]: political parties usually growing more extreme, right? More reactionary elements sort of capturing

01:29:57.820 --> 01:30:03.340
[Guest]: or whatever, what do you want to call them? More purist elements, capturing power within the party.

01:30:03.340 --> 01:30:06.540
[Amit Varma]: Do you have any thoughts on why that is? Because typically, like in public choice theory,

01:30:06.540 --> 01:30:10.940
[Amit Varma]: what you learn is you learn the medium voter theorem, which is basically that even in the US,

01:30:10.940 --> 01:30:14.460
[Amit Varma]: you have the Democratic and the Republican Party, every election in the primaries,

01:30:14.460 --> 01:30:18.140
[Amit Varma]: they'll go towards the extremes to win the primary votes of the committed guys.

01:30:18.140 --> 01:30:21.900
[Amit Varma]: But in the general election, they'll immediately swing towards the middle. And you've seen that

01:30:21.900 --> 01:30:27.500
[Amit Varma]: trend changing, where more and more, the voters themselves tend to swing to the extremes. And

01:30:27.500 --> 01:30:31.900
[Amit Varma]: that brings a guy like Trump into power. And maybe Bernie Sanders would have given on the other

01:30:31.900 --> 01:30:36.940
[Amit Varma]: extreme would have given him a tougher fight than Hillary Clinton. And we don't know. So why does

01:30:36.940 --> 01:30:41.260
[Guest]: the median voter theorem no longer work? Two or three things I can think of.

01:30:42.940 --> 01:30:49.500
[Guest]: One, as with a lot of other theorizing in, especially in public choice economics, right?

01:30:51.020 --> 01:30:56.860
[Guest]: We should not assume perfect information or even unmanipulated flow of information.

01:30:56.860 --> 01:30:59.340
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, there's rational ignorance and so on.

01:30:59.340 --> 01:31:01.820
[Guest]: There's one set of issues around basically,

01:31:05.100 --> 01:31:09.340
[Guest]: who is able to get information out there, who is able to get the narrative out there.

01:31:09.340 --> 01:31:15.580
[Guest]: Trump visibly, I mean, you if nothing else, you have to give him credit for completely hijacking

01:31:15.580 --> 01:31:20.460
[Guest]: the media's decision making cycle. Right. And for doing that masterfully. Yeah. Right.

01:31:20.460 --> 01:31:22.700
[Amit Varma]: He perhaps unintentionally again.

01:31:22.700 --> 01:31:25.980
[Amit Varma]: Oh, that's one where I think he knew the rules of that game. And like,

01:31:25.980 --> 01:31:28.060
[Guest]: he knew how to spin them to his favor. Right.

01:31:28.060 --> 01:31:33.020
[Amit Varma]: So one of his metrics was how much news I get, how much, you know, airtime I get.

01:31:33.020 --> 01:31:37.020
[Guest]: Yeah, no, I mean, he I mean, he's confessed in like other speeches since that, like,

01:31:38.540 --> 01:31:45.020
[Guest]: he basically decided what he would make his slogans based on what the crowd was responding to.

01:31:45.020 --> 01:31:50.220
[Guest]: Right. So one to do with flow of information and media, one to do with especially in democracies.

01:31:51.420 --> 01:31:54.620
[Amit Varma]: All of which are forever held, though they've held over the last few decades,

01:31:54.620 --> 01:32:01.020
[Amit Varma]: imperfect information, rational ignorance, the tendency to prefer simple narratives over complex

01:32:01.020 --> 01:32:06.780
[Amit Varma]: ones. And yet the median voter theorem held and now it suddenly doesn't. Now it's profitable for

01:32:06.780 --> 01:32:09.180
[Amit Varma]: you to go to the extremes in the general elections.

01:32:09.180 --> 01:32:18.220
[Guest]: So I suspect and I'm not very well read in this. So I sort of have to caveat. But I suspect that

01:32:18.220 --> 01:32:27.660
[Guest]: the development from earlier is the fact that the sources of information themselves have fragmented

01:32:27.660 --> 01:32:37.340
[Guest]: and tribalized. And that you're no longer arguing over what is a good response to an agreed reality.

01:32:37.340 --> 01:32:43.740
[Guest]: Right. You're arguing over like, a reality that itself is partisanly constructed.

01:32:43.740 --> 01:32:49.980
[Guest]: Right. And, you know, might not bear all but the most passing resemblance to

01:32:50.700 --> 01:32:57.020
[Guest]: what the other person sees. Which I think would start leaning you towards greater

01:32:58.780 --> 01:33:00.860
[Unknown]: Polarization. Polarization, exactly.

01:33:02.620 --> 01:33:06.860
[Guest]: There's an entire set of theories, at least within the US around what kind of voters are

01:33:06.860 --> 01:33:12.780
[Guest]: more likely to actually go out and vote or not. And the fact that like, you know, it's

01:33:12.780 --> 01:33:19.020
[Guest]: the extremes that actually vote on either side or on each side of how many ever sided a distribution

01:33:19.020 --> 01:33:23.500
[Guest]: this is. And that the median actually tends to sort of assume that they don't have much

01:33:23.500 --> 01:33:27.500
[Guest]: of a swing capacity and not. That's very well put. And I've argued before

01:33:27.500 --> 01:33:32.780
[Amit Varma]: in columns that social media has actually exacerbated this tribalism and polarization

01:33:32.780 --> 01:33:38.540
[Amit Varma]: and this creation of alternative narratives. I may have taken a lot of your time today. And,

01:33:38.540 --> 01:33:41.980
[Amit Varma]: you know, thanks so much for your patience. And thanks so much for coming on the show.

01:33:41.980 --> 01:33:45.340
[Amit Varma]: Thanks so much for coming on the scene in the unseen. I learned a lot from you and I

01:33:45.340 --> 01:34:13.660
[Amit Varma]: hope you'll come back soon. I would love to be back. Thank you.

01:34:15.340 --> 01:34:23.660
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

01:34:45.340 --> 01:34:49.660
[Unknown]: Thank you.

01:35:15.340 --> 01:35:21.660
[Unknown]: Thank you.

